       "  'keywords': ['custom',\n",
       "   'adversary',\n",
       "   'compress',\n",
       "   'encrypt',\n",
       "   'data',\n",
       "   'collected',\n",
       "   'prior',\n",
       "   'exfiltration',\n",
       "   'method',\n",
       "   'choose'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': An adversary compress or encrypt data that is collected prior to exfiltration using a custom method. choose to use custom archival methods, such as encryption with XOR or stream ciphers implemented with no external library or utility references. Custom implementations of well-known compression algorithms have also been used.},\n",
       " 'T1578': {'name': 'Modify Cloud Compute Infrastructure',\n",
       "  'description': \"An adversary attempt to modify a cloud account's compute service infrastructure to evade defenses. A modification to the compute service infrastructure include the creation, deletion, or modification of one or more components such as compute instances, virtual machines, and snapshots. Permissions gained from the modification of infrastructure components bypass restrictions that prevent access to existing infrastructure. Modifying infrastructure components also allow an adversary to evade detection and remove evidence of their presence.\",\n",
       "  'tactics': ['defense-evasion'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['infrastructure',\n",
       "   'compute',\n",
       "   'modification',\n",
       "   'components',\n",
       "   'adversary',\n",
       "   'service',\n",
       "   'evade',\n",
       "   'attempt',\n",
       "   'modify',\n",
       "   'cloud'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': An adversary attempt to modify a cloud account's compute service infrastructure to evade defenses. A modification to the compute service infrastructure include the creation, deletion, or modification of one or more components such as compute instances, virtual machines, and snapshots. Permissions gained from the modification of infrastructure components bypass restrictions that prevent access to existing infrastructure. Modifying infrastructure components also allow an adversary to evade detection and remove evidence of their presence.},\n",
       " 'T1584.008': {'name': 'Network Devices',\n",
       "  'description': \"compromise third-party network devices that be used during targeting. Network devices, such as small office/home office (SOHO) routers, be compromised where the adversary's ultimate goal is not Initial Access to that environment -- instead leveraging these devices to support additional targeting. Once an adversary has control, compromised network devices be used to launch additional operations, such as hosting payloads for Phishing campaigns (i.e., Link Target) or enabling the required access to execute Content Injection operations. also be able to harvest reusable credentials (i.e., Valid Accounts) from compromised network devices. often target Internet-facing edge devices and related network appliances that specifically do not support robust host-based defenses. Compromised network devices be used to support subsequent Command and Control activity, such as Hide Infrastructure through an established Proxy and/or Botnet network.\",\n",
       "  'tactics': ['resource-development'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['network',\n",
       "   'devices',\n",
       "   'compromised',\n",
       "   'support',\n",
       "   'targeting',\n",
       "   'office',\n",
       "   'adversary',\n",
       "   'access',\n",
       "   'additional',\n",
       "   'control'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': compromise third-party network devices that be used during targeting. Network devices, such as small office/home office (SOHO) routers, be compromised where the adversary's ultimate goal is not Initial Access to that environment -- instead leveraging these devices to support additional targeting. Once an adversary has control, compromised network devices be used to launch additional operations, such as hosting payloads for Phishing campaigns (i.e., Link Target) or enabling the required access to execute Content Injection operations. also be able to harvest reusable credentials (i.e., Valid Accounts) from compromised network devices. often target Internet-facing edge devices and related network appliances that specifically do not support robust host-based defenses. Compromised network devices be used to support subsequent Command and Control activity, such as Hide Infrastructure through an established Proxy and/or Botnet network.},\n",
       " 'T1583.008': {'name': 'Malvertising',\n",
       "  'description': \"purchase online advertisements that be abused to distribute malware to victims. Ads be purchased to plant as well as favorably position artifacts in specific locations online, such as prominently placed within search engine results. These ads make it more difficult for users to distinguish between actual search results and advertisements. Purchased ads also target specific audiences using the advertising network’s capabilities, potentially further taking advantage of the trust inherently given to search engines and popular websites. purchase ads and other resources to help distribute artifacts containing malicious code to victims. Purchased ads attempt to impersonate or spoof well-known brands. For example, these spoofed ads trick victims into clicking the ad which then send them to a malicious domain that be a clone of official websites containing trojanized versions of the advertised software. Adversary’s efforts to create malicious domains and purchase advertisements also be automated at scale to better resist cleanup efforts. Malvertising be used to support Drive-by Target and Drive-by Compromise, potentially requiring limited interaction from the user if the ad contains code/exploits that infect the target system's web browser. also employ several techniques to evade detection by the advertising network. For example, dynamically route ad clicks to send automated crawler/policy enforcer traffic to benign sites while validating potential targets then sending victims referred from real ad clicks to malicious pages. This infection vector therefore remain hidden from the ad network as well as any visitor not reaching the malicious sites with a valid identifier from clicking on the advertisement. Other tricks, such as intentional typos to avoid brand reputation monitoring, also be used to evade automated detection.\",\n",
       "  'tactics': ['resource-development'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['ads',\n",
       "   'malicious',\n",
       "   'victims',\n",
       "   'purchase',\n",
       "   'advertisements',\n",
       "   'purchased',\n",
       "   'search',\n",
       "   'target',\n",
       "   'network',\n",
       "   'automated'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': purchase online advertisements that be abused to distribute malware to victims. Ads be purchased to plant as well as favorably position artifacts in specific locations online, such as prominently placed within search engine results. These ads make it more difficult for users to distinguish between actual search results and advertisements. Purchased ads also target specific audiences using the advertising network’s capabilities, potentially further taking advantage of the trust inherently given to search engines and popular websites. purchase ads and other resources to help distribute artifacts containing malicious code to victims. Purchased ads attempt to impersonate or spoof well-known brands. For example, these spoofed ads trick victims into clicking the ad which then send them to a malicious domain that be a clone of official websites containing trojanized versions of the advertised software. Adversary’s efforts to create malicious domains and purchase advertisements also be automated at scale to better resist cleanup efforts. Malvertising be used to support Drive-by Target and Drive-by Compromise, potentially requiring limited interaction from the user if the ad contains code/exploits that infect the target system's web browser. also employ several techniques to evade detection by the advertising network. For example, dynamically route ad clicks to send automated crawler/policy enforcer traffic to benign sites while validating potential targets then sending victims referred from real ad clicks to malicious pages. This infection vector therefore remain hidden from the ad network as well as any visitor not reaching the malicious sites with a valid identifier from clicking on the advertisement. Other tricks, such as intentional typos to avoid brand reputation monitoring, also be used to evade automated detection.},\n",
       " 'T1069': {'name': 'Permission Groups Discovery',\n",
       "  'description': 'attempt to discover group and permission settings. This information help determine which user accounts and groups are available, the membership of users in particular groups, and which users and groups have elevated permissions. attempt to discover group permission settings in many different ways. This data provide the adversary with information about the compromised environment that be used in follow-on activity and targeting.',\n",
