       "  'spacy_doc': reduce the level of effort required to decrypt data transmitted over the network by reducing the cipher strength of encrypted communications. weaken the encryption software on a compromised network device by reducing the key size used by the software to convert plaintext to ciphertext (e.g., from hundreds or thousands of bytes to just a couple of bytes). As a result, dramatically reduce the amount of effort needed to decrypt the protected information without the key. modify the key size used and other encryption parameters using specialized commands in a Network Device CLI introduced to the system through Modify System Image to change the configuration of the device.},\n",
       " 'T1070.003': {'name': 'Clear Command History',\n",
       "  'description': \"In addition to clearing system logs, an adversary clear the command history of a compromised account to conceal the actions undertaken during an intrusion. Various command interpreters keep track of the commands users type in their terminal so that users retrace what they've done. On Linux and macOS, these command histories be accessed in a few different ways. While logged in, this command history is tracked in a file pointed to by the environment variable HISTFILE. When a user logs off a system, this information is flushed to a file in the user's home directory called ~/.bash_history. The benefit of this is that it allows users to go back to commands they've used before in different sessions. delete their commands from these logs by manually clearing the history (history -c) or deleting the bash history file rm ~/.bash_history. also leverage a Network Device CLI on network devices to clear command history data (clear logging and/or clear history). On Windows hosts, PowerShell has two different command history providers: the built-in history and the command history managed by the PSReadLine module. The built-in history only tracks the commands used in the current session. This command history is not available to other sessions and is deleted when the session ends. The PSReadLine command history tracks the commands used in all PowerShell sessions and writes them to a file ($env:APPDATA\\\\Microsoft\\\\Windows\\\\PowerShell\\\\PSReadLine\\\\ConsoleHost_history.txt by default). This history file is available to all sessions and contains all past history since the file is not deleted when the session ends. run the PowerShell command Clear-History to flush the entire command history from a current PowerShell session. This, however, will not delete/flush the ConsoleHost_history.txt file. also delete the ConsoleHost_history.txt file or edit its contents to hide PowerShell commands they have run.\",\n",
       "  'tactics': ['defense-evasion'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['history',\n",
       "   'command',\n",
       "   'file',\n",
       "   'commands',\n",
       "   'clear',\n",
       "   'powershell',\n",
       "   'sessions',\n",
       "   'session',\n",
       "   'logs',\n",
       "   'users'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': In addition to clearing system logs, an adversary clear the command history of a compromised account to conceal the actions undertaken during an intrusion. Various command interpreters keep track of the commands users type in their terminal so that users retrace what they've done. On Linux and macOS, these command histories be accessed in a few different ways. While logged in, this command history is tracked in a file pointed to by the environment variable HISTFILE. When a user logs off a system, this information is flushed to a file in the user's home directory called ~/.bash_history. The benefit of this is that it allows users to go back to commands they've used before in different sessions. delete their commands from these logs by manually clearing the history (history -c) or deleting the bash history file rm ~/.bash_history. also leverage a Network Device CLI on network devices to clear command history data (clear logging and/or clear history). On Windows hosts, PowerShell has two different command history providers: the built-in history and the command history managed by the PSReadLine module. The built-in history only tracks the commands used in the current session. This command history is not available to other sessions and is deleted when the session ends. The PSReadLine command history tracks the commands used in all PowerShell sessions and writes them to a file ($env:APPDATA\\Microsoft\\Windows\\PowerShell\\PSReadLine\\ConsoleHost_history.txt by default). This history file is available to all sessions and contains all past history since the file is not deleted when the session ends. run the PowerShell command Clear-History to flush the entire command history from a current PowerShell session. This, however, will not delete/flush the ConsoleHost_history.txt file. also delete the ConsoleHost_history.txt file or edit its contents to hide PowerShell commands they have run.},\n",
       " 'T1202': {'name': 'Indirect Command Execution',\n",
       "  'description': 'abuse utilities that allow for command execution to bypass security restrictions that limit the use of command-line interpreters. Various Windows utilities be used to execute commands, without invoking cmd. For example, Forfiles, the Program Compatibility Assistant (pcalua.exe), components of the Windows Subsystem for Linux (WSL), Scriptrunner.exe, as well as other utilities invoke the execution of programs and commands from a Command and Scripting Interpreter, Run window, or via scripts. abuse these features for Defense Evasion, specifically to perform arbitrary execution while subverting detections and/or mitigation controls (such as Group Policy) that limit/prevent the usage of cmd or file extensions more commonly associated with malicious payloads.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['defense-evasion'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['utilities',\n",
       "   'command',\n",
       "   'execution',\n",
       "   'abuse',\n",
       "   'limit',\n",
       "   'windows',\n",
       "   'commands',\n",
       "   'cmd',\n",
       "   'allow',\n",
       "   'bypass'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': abuse utilities that allow for command execution to bypass security restrictions that limit the use of command-line interpreters. Various Windows utilities be used to execute commands, without invoking cmd. For example, Forfiles, the Program Compatibility Assistant (pcalua.exe), components of the Windows Subsystem for Linux (WSL), Scriptrunner.exe, as well as other utilities invoke the execution of programs and commands from a Command and Scripting Interpreter, Run window, or via scripts. abuse these features for Defense Evasion, specifically to perform arbitrary execution while subverting detections and/or mitigation controls (such as Group Policy) that limit/prevent the usage of cmd or file extensions more commonly associated with malicious payloads.},\n",
       " 'T1024': {'name': 'Custom Cryptographic Protocol',\n",
       "  'description': 'use a custom cryptographic protocol or algorithm to hide command and control traffic. A simple scheme, such as XOR-ing the plaintext with a fixed key, will produce a very weak ciphertext. Custom encryption schemes vary in sophistication. Analysis and reverse engineering of malware samples be enough to discover the algorithm and encryption key used. Some also attempt to implement their own version of a well-known cryptographic algorithm instead of using a known implementation library, which lead to unintentional errors.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['command-and-control'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['algorithm',\n",
       "   'custom',\n",
       "   'cryptographic',\n",
       "   'key',\n",
       "   'encryption',\n",
       "   'known',\n",
       "   'use',\n",
       "   'protocol',\n",
       "   'hide',\n",
       "   'command'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': use a custom cryptographic protocol or algorithm to hide command and control traffic. A simple scheme, such as XOR-ing the plaintext with a fixed key, will produce a very weak ciphertext. Custom encryption schemes vary in sophistication. Analysis and reverse engineering of malware samples be enough to discover the algorithm and encryption key used. Some also attempt to implement their own version of a well-known cryptographic algorithm instead of using a known implementation library, which lead to unintentional errors.},\n",
       " 'T1536': {'name': 'Revert Cloud Instance',\n",
       "  'description': 'An adversary revert changes made to a cloud instance after they have performed malicious activities in attempt to evade detection and remove evidence of their presence. In highly virtualized environments, such as cloud-based infrastructure, this be accomplished by restoring virtual machine (VM) or data storage snapshots through the cloud management dashboard or cloud APIs. Another variation of this technique is to utilize temporary storage attached to the compute instance. Most cloud providers provide various types of storage including persistent, local, and/or ephemeral, with the ephemeral types often reset upon stop/restart of the VM.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['defense-evasion'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['cloud',\n",
       "   'storage',\n",
       "   'instance',\n",
       "   'types',\n",
       "   'ephemeral',\n",
       "   'adversary',\n",
       "   'revert',\n",
       "   'changes',\n",
       "   'performed',\n",
       "   'malicious'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': An adversary revert changes made to a cloud instance after they have performed malicious activities in attempt to evade detection and remove evidence of their presence. In highly virtualized environments, such as cloud-based infrastructure, this be accomplished by restoring virtual machine (VM) or data storage snapshots through the cloud management dashboard or cloud APIs. Another variation of this technique is to utilize temporary storage attached to the compute instance. Most cloud providers provide various types of storage including persistent, local, and/or ephemeral, with the ephemeral types often reset upon stop/restart of the VM.},\n",
       " 'T1091': {'name': 'Replication Through Removable Media',\n",
       "  'description': \"move onto systems, those on disconnected or air-gapped networks, by copying malware to removable media and taking advantage of Autorun features when the media is inserted into a system and executes. In the case of Lateral Movement, this occur through modification of executable files stored on removable media or by copying malware and renaming it to look like a legitimate file to trick users into executing it on a separate system. In the case of Initial Access, this occur through manual manipulation of the media, modification of systems used to initially format the media, or modification to the media's firmware itself. Mobile devices also be used to infect PCs with malware if connected via USB. This infection be achieved using devices (Android, iOS, etc.) and, in some instances, USB charging cables. For example, when a smartphone is connected to a system, it appear to be mounted similar to a USB-connected disk drive. If malware that is compatible with the connected system is on the mobile device, the malware infect the machine (especially if Autorun features are enabled).\",\n",
       "  'tactics': ['initial-access', 'lateral-movement'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['media',\n",
       "   'malware',\n",
       "   'system',\n",
       "   'connected',\n",
       "   'modification',\n",
       "   'usb',\n",
       "   'systems',\n",
       "   'copying',\n",
       "   'removable',\n",
       "   'autorun'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': move onto systems, those on disconnected or air-gapped networks, by copying malware to removable media and taking advantage of Autorun features when the media is inserted into a system and executes. In the case of Lateral Movement, this occur through modification of executable files stored on removable media or by copying malware and renaming it to look like a legitimate file to trick users into executing it on a separate system. In the case of Initial Access, this occur through manual manipulation of the media, modification of systems used to initially format the media, or modification to the media's firmware itself. Mobile devices also be used to infect PCs with malware if connected via USB. This infection be achieved using devices (Android, iOS, etc.) and, in some instances, USB charging cables. For example, when a smartphone is connected to a system, it appear to be mounted similar to a USB-connected disk drive. If malware that is compatible with the connected system is on the mobile device, the malware infect the machine (especially if Autorun features are enabled).},\n",
       " 'T1005': {'name': 'Data from Local System',\n",
       "  'description': 'search local system sources, such as file systems and configuration files or local databases, to find files of interest and sensitive data prior to Exfiltration. do this using a Command and Scripting Interpreter, such as cmd as well as a Network Device CLI, which have functionality to interact with the file system to gather information. also use Automated Collection on the local system.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['collection'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['local',\n",
       "   'system',\n",
       "   'file',\n",
       "   'files',\n",
       "   'search',\n",
       "   'sources',\n",
       "   'systems',\n",
       "   'configuration',\n",
       "   'databases',\n",
       "   'find'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': search local system sources, such as file systems and configuration files or local databases, to find files of interest and sensitive data prior to Exfiltration. do this using a Command and Scripting Interpreter, such as cmd as well as a Network Device CLI, which have functionality to interact with the file system to gather information. also use Automated Collection on the local system.},\n",
       " 'T1140': {'name': 'Deobfuscate/Decode Files or Information',\n",
       "  'description': \"use Obfuscated Files or Information to hide artifacts of an intrusion from analysis. They require separate mechanisms to decode or deobfuscate that information depending on how they intend to use it. Methods for doing that include built-in functionality of malware or by using utilities present on the system. One such example is the use of certutil to decode a remote access tool portable executable file that has been hidden inside a certificate file. Another example is using the Windows copy /b command to reassemble binary fragments into a malicious payload. Sometimes a user's action be required to open it for deobfuscation or decryption as part of User Execution. The user also be required to input a password to open a password protected compressed/encrypted file that was provided by the adversary.\",\n",
       "  'tactics': ['defense-evasion'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['use',\n",
       "   'file',\n",
       "   'user',\n",
       "   'information',\n",
       "   'decode',\n",
       "   'example',\n",
       "   'required',\n",
       "   'open',\n",
       "   'password',\n",
       "   'obfuscated'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': use Obfuscated Files or Information to hide artifacts of an intrusion from analysis. They require separate mechanisms to decode or deobfuscate that information depending on how they intend to use it. Methods for doing that include built-in functionality of malware or by using utilities present on the system. One such example is the use of certutil to decode a remote access tool portable executable file that has been hidden inside a certificate file. Another example is using the Windows copy /b command to reassemble binary fragments into a malicious payload. Sometimes a user's action be required to open it for deobfuscation or decryption as part of User Execution. The user also be required to input a password to open a password protected compressed/encrypted file that was provided by the adversary.},\n",
       " 'T1137.005': {'name': 'Outlook Rules',\n",
       "  'description': 'abuse Microsoft Outlook rules to obtain persistence on a compromised system. Outlook rules allow a user to define automated behavior to manage email messages. A benign rule , for example, automatically move an email to a particular folder in Outlook if it contains specific words from a specific sender. Malicious Outlook rules be created that trigger code execution when an adversary sends a specifically crafted email to that user. Once malicious rules have been added to the user’s mailbox, they will be loaded when Outlook is started. Malicious rules will execute when an adversary sends a specifically crafted email to the user.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['persistence'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['outlook',\n",
       "   'rules',\n",
       "   'user',\n",
       "   'email',\n",
       "   'malicious',\n",
       "   'specific',\n",
       "   'adversary',\n",
       "   'sends',\n",
       "   'specifically',\n",
       "   'crafted'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': abuse Microsoft Outlook rules to obtain persistence on a compromised system. Outlook rules allow a user to define automated behavior to manage email messages. A benign rule , for example, automatically move an email to a particular folder in Outlook if it contains specific words from a specific sender. Malicious Outlook rules be created that trigger code execution when an adversary sends a specifically crafted email to that user. Once malicious rules have been added to the user’s mailbox, they will be loaded when Outlook is started. Malicious rules will execute when an adversary sends a specifically crafted email to the user.},\n",
       " 'T1562': {'name': 'Impair Defenses',\n",
       "  'description': 'maliciously modify components of a victim environment in order to hinder or disable defensive mechanisms. This not only involves impairing preventative defenses, such as firewalls and anti-virus, but also detection capabilities that defenders use to audit activity and identify malicious behavior. This also span both native defenses as well as supplemental capabilities installed by users and administrators. also impair routine operations that contribute to defensive hygiene, such as blocking users from logging out, preventing a system from shutting down, or disabling or modifying the update process. also target event aggregation and analysis mechanisms, or otherwise disrupt these procedures by altering other system components. These restrictions further enable malicious operations as well as the continued propagation of incidents.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['defense-evasion'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['components',\n",
       "   'defensive',\n",
       "   'mechanisms',\n",
       "   'defenses',\n",
       "   'capabilities',\n",
       "   'malicious',\n",
       "   'users',\n",
       "   'operations',\n",
       "   'system',\n",
       "   'maliciously'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': maliciously modify components of a victim environment in order to hinder or disable defensive mechanisms. This not only involves impairing preventative defenses, such as firewalls and anti-virus, but also detection capabilities that defenders use to audit activity and identify malicious behavior. This also span both native defenses as well as supplemental capabilities installed by users and administrators. also impair routine operations that contribute to defensive hygiene, such as blocking users from logging out, preventing a system from shutting down, or disabling or modifying the update process. also target event aggregation and analysis mechanisms, or otherwise disrupt these procedures by altering other system components. These restrictions further enable malicious operations as well as the continued propagation of incidents.},\n",
       " 'T1586.003': {'name': 'Cloud Accounts',\n",
       "  'description': 'compromise cloud accounts that be used during targeting. use compromised cloud accounts to further their operations, including leveraging cloud storage services such as Dropbox, Microsoft OneDrive, or AWS S3 buckets for Exfiltration to Cloud Storage or to Upload Tools. Cloud accounts also be used in the acquisition of infrastructure, such as Virtual Private Servers or Serverless infrastructure. Additionally, cloud-based messaging services such as Twilio, SendGrid, AWS End User Messaging, AWS SNS (Simple Notification Service), or AWS SES (Simple Email Service) be leveraged for spam or Phishing. Compromising cloud accounts allow to develop sophisticated capabilities without managing their own servers. A variety of methods exist for compromising cloud accounts, such as gathering credentials via Phishing for Information, purchasing credentials from third-party sites, conducting Password Spraying attacks, or attempting to Steal Application Access Tokens. Prior to compromising cloud accounts, conduct Reconnaissance to inform decisions about which accounts to compromise to further their operation. In some cases, target privileged service provider accounts with the intent of leveraging a Trusted Relationship between service providers and their customers.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['resource-development'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['cloud',\n",
       "   'accounts',\n",
       "   'aws',\n",
       "   'service',\n",
       "   'compromising',\n",
       "   'compromise',\n",
       "   'leveraging',\n",
       "   'storage',\n",
       "   'services',\n",
       "   'infrastructure'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': compromise cloud accounts that be used during targeting. use compromised cloud accounts to further their operations, including leveraging cloud storage services such as Dropbox, Microsoft OneDrive, or AWS S3 buckets for Exfiltration to Cloud Storage or to Upload Tools. Cloud accounts also be used in the acquisition of infrastructure, such as Virtual Private Servers or Serverless infrastructure. Additionally, cloud-based messaging services such as Twilio, SendGrid, AWS End User Messaging, AWS SNS (Simple Notification Service), or AWS SES (Simple Email Service) be leveraged for spam or Phishing. Compromising cloud accounts allow to develop sophisticated capabilities without managing their own servers. A variety of methods exist for compromising cloud accounts, such as gathering credentials via Phishing for Information, purchasing credentials from third-party sites, conducting Password Spraying attacks, or attempting to Steal Application Access Tokens. Prior to compromising cloud accounts, conduct Reconnaissance to inform decisions about which accounts to compromise to further their operation. In some cases, target privileged service provider accounts with the intent of leveraging a Trusted Relationship between service providers and their customers.},\n",
       " 'T1586.002': {'name': 'Email Accounts',\n",
       "  'description': 'compromise email accounts that be used during targeting. use compromised email accounts to further their operations, such as leveraging them to conduct Phishing for Information, Phishing, or large-scale spam email campaigns. Utilizing an existing persona with a compromised email account engender a level of trust in a potential victim if they have a relationship with, or knowledge of, the compromised persona. Compromised email accounts also be used in the acquisition of infrastructure (ex: Domains). A variety of methods exist for compromising email accounts, such as gathering credentials via Phishing for Information, purchasing credentials from third-party sites, brute forcing credentials (ex: password reuse from breach credential dumps), or paying employees, suppliers or business partners for access to credentials. Prior to compromising email accounts, conduct Reconnaissance to inform decisions about which accounts to compromise to further their operation. target compromising well-known email accounts or domains from which malicious spam or Phishing emails evade reputation-based email filtering rules. use a compromised email account to hijack existing email threads with targets of interest.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['resource-development'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['email',\n",
       "   'accounts',\n",
       "   'compromised',\n",
       "   'phishing',\n",
       "   'credentials',\n",
       "   'compromising',\n",
       "   'compromise',\n",
       "   'use',\n",
       "   'conduct',\n",
       "   'information'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': compromise email accounts that be used during targeting. use compromised email accounts to further their operations, such as leveraging them to conduct Phishing for Information, Phishing, or large-scale spam email campaigns. Utilizing an existing persona with a compromised email account engender a level of trust in a potential victim if they have a relationship with, or knowledge of, the compromised persona. Compromised email accounts also be used in the acquisition of infrastructure (ex: Domains). A variety of methods exist for compromising email accounts, such as gathering credentials via Phishing for Information, purchasing credentials from third-party sites, brute forcing credentials (ex: password reuse from breach credential dumps), or paying employees, suppliers or business partners for access to credentials. Prior to compromising email accounts, conduct Reconnaissance to inform decisions about which accounts to compromise to further their operation. target compromising well-known email accounts or domains from which malicious spam or Phishing emails evade reputation-based email filtering rules. use a compromised email account to hijack existing email threads with targets of interest.},\n",
       " 'T1098.007': {'name': 'Additional Local or Domain Groups',\n",
       "  'description': 'An adversary add additional local or domain groups to an adversary-controlled account to maintain persistent access to a system or domain. On Windows, accounts use the net localgroup and net group commands to add existing users to local and domain groups. On Linux, use the usermod command for the same purpose. For example, accounts be added to the local administrators group on Windows devices to maintain elevated privileges. They also be added to the Remote Desktop Users group, which allows them to leverage Remote Desktop Protocol to log into the endpoints in the future. On Linux, accounts be added to the sudoers group, allowing them to persistently leverage Sudo and Sudo Caching for elevated privileges. In Windows environments, machine accounts also be added to domain groups. This allows the local SYSTEM account to gain privileges on the domain.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['persistence', 'privilege-escalation'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['domain',\n",
       "   'local',\n",
       "   'accounts',\n",
       "   'group',\n",
       "   'added',\n",
       "   'groups',\n",
       "   'windows',\n",
       "   'privileges',\n",
       "   'adversary',\n",
       "   'add'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': An adversary add additional local or domain groups to an adversary-controlled account to maintain persistent access to a system or domain. On Windows, accounts use the net localgroup and net group commands to add existing users to local and domain groups. On Linux, use the usermod command for the same purpose. For example, accounts be added to the local administrators group on Windows devices to maintain elevated privileges. They also be added to the Remote Desktop Users group, which allows them to leverage Remote Desktop Protocol to log into the endpoints in the future. On Linux, accounts be added to the sudoers group, allowing them to persistently leverage Sudo and Sudo Caching for elevated privileges. In Windows environments, machine accounts also be added to domain groups. This allows the local SYSTEM account to gain privileges on the domain.},\n",
       " 'T1608.001': {'name': 'Upload Malware',\n",
       "  'description': 'upload malware to third-party or adversary controlled infrastructure to make it accessible during targeting. Malicious software include payloads, droppers, post-compromise tools, backdoors, and a variety of other malicious content. upload malware to support their operations, such as making a payload available to a victim network to enable Ingress Tool Transfer by placing it on an Internet accessible web server. Malware be placed on infrastructure that was previously purchased/rented by the adversary (Acquire Infrastructure) or was otherwise compromised by them (Compromise Infrastructure). Malware also be staged on web services, such as GitHub or Pastebin, or hosted on the InterPlanetary File System (IPFS), where decentralized content storage makes the removal of malicious files difficult. upload backdoored files, such as application binaries, virtual machine images, or container images, to third-party software stores or repositories (ex: GitHub, CNET, AWS Community AMIs, Docker Hub). By chance encounter, victims directly download/install these backdoored files via User Execution. Masquerading increase the chance of users mistakenly executing these files.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['resource-development'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['malware',\n",
       "   'infrastructure',\n",
       "   'files',\n",
       "   'upload',\n",
       "   'malicious',\n",
       "   'party',\n",
       "   'adversary',\n",
       "   'accessible',\n",
       "   'software',\n",
       "   'compromise'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': upload malware to third-party or adversary controlled infrastructure to make it accessible during targeting. Malicious software include payloads, droppers, post-compromise tools, backdoors, and a variety of other malicious content. upload malware to support their operations, such as making a payload available to a victim network to enable Ingress Tool Transfer by placing it on an Internet accessible web server. Malware be placed on infrastructure that was previously purchased/rented by the adversary (Acquire Infrastructure) or was otherwise compromised by them (Compromise Infrastructure). Malware also be staged on web services, such as GitHub or Pastebin, or hosted on the InterPlanetary File System (IPFS), where decentralized content storage makes the removal of malicious files difficult. upload backdoored files, such as application binaries, virtual machine images, or container images, to third-party software stores or repositories (ex: GitHub, CNET, AWS Community AMIs, Docker Hub). By chance encounter, victims directly download/install these backdoored files via User Execution. Masquerading increase the chance of users mistakenly executing these files.},\n",
       " 'T1195': {'name': 'Supply Chain Compromise',\n",
       "  'description': 'manipulate products or product delivery mechanisms prior to receipt by a final consumer for the purpose of data or system compromise. Supply chain compromise take place at any stage of the supply chain including: * Manipulation of development tools * Manipulation of a development environment * Manipulation of source code repositories (public or private) * Manipulation of source code in open-source dependencies * Manipulation of software update/distribution mechanisms * Compromised/infected system images (multiple cases of removable media infected at the factory) * Replacement of legitimate software with modified versions * Sales of modified/counterfeit products to legitimate distributors * Shipment interdiction While supply chain compromise impact any component of hardware or software, looking to gain execution have often focused on malicious additions to legitimate software in software distribution or update channels. Targeting be specific to a desired victim set or malicious software be distributed to a broad set of consumers but only move on to additional tactics on specific victims. Popular open source projects that are used as dependencies in many applications also be targeted as a means to add malicious code to users of the dependency.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['initial-access'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['software',\n",
       "   'manipulation',\n",
       "   'source',\n",
       "   'compromise',\n",
       "   'supply',\n",
       "   'chain',\n",
       "   'code',\n",
       "   'legitimate',\n",
       "   'malicious',\n",
       "   'products'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': manipulate products or product delivery mechanisms prior to receipt by a final consumer for the purpose of data or system compromise. Supply chain compromise take place at any stage of the supply chain including: * Manipulation of development tools * Manipulation of a development environment * Manipulation of source code repositories (public or private) * Manipulation of source code in open-source dependencies * Manipulation of software update/distribution mechanisms * Compromised/infected system images (multiple cases of removable media infected at the factory) * Replacement of legitimate software with modified versions * Sales of modified/counterfeit products to legitimate distributors * Shipment interdiction While supply chain compromise impact any component of hardware or software, looking to gain execution have often focused on malicious additions to legitimate software in software distribution or update channels. Targeting be specific to a desired victim set or malicious software be distributed to a broad set of consumers but only move on to additional tactics on specific victims. Popular open source projects that are used as dependencies in many applications also be targeted as a means to add malicious code to users of the dependency.},\n",
       " 'T1190': {'name': 'Exploit Public-Facing Application',\n",
       "  'description': 'attempt to exploit a weakness in an Internet-facing host or system to initially access a network. The weakness in the system be a software bug, a temporary glitch, or a misconfiguration. Exploited applications are often websites/web servers, but also include databases (like SQL), standard services (like SMB or SSH), network device administration and management protocols (like SNMP and Smart Install), and any other system with Internet-accessible open sockets. Depending on the flaw being exploited this also involve Exploitation for Defense Evasion or Exploitation for Client Execution. If an application is hosted on cloud-based infrastructure and/or is containerized, then exploiting it lead to compromise of the underlying instance or container. This allow an adversary a path to access the cloud or container APIs (e.g., via the Cloud Instance Metadata API), exploit container host access via Escape to Host, or take advantage of weak identity and access management policies. also exploit edge network infrastructure and related appliances, specifically targeting devices that do not support robust host-based defenses. For websites and databases, the OWASP top 10 and CWE top 25 highlight the most common web-based vulnerabilities.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['initial-access'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['host',\n",
       "   'access',\n",
       "   'exploit',\n",
       "   'system',\n",
       "   'network',\n",
       "   'like',\n",
       "   'cloud',\n",
       "   'based',\n",
       "   'container',\n",
       "   'weakness'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': attempt to exploit a weakness in an Internet-facing host or system to initially access a network. The weakness in the system be a software bug, a temporary glitch, or a misconfiguration. Exploited applications are often websites/web servers, but also include databases (like SQL), standard services (like SMB or SSH), network device administration and management protocols (like SNMP and Smart Install), and any other system with Internet-accessible open sockets. Depending on the flaw being exploited this also involve Exploitation for Defense Evasion or Exploitation for Client Execution. If an application is hosted on cloud-based infrastructure and/or is containerized, then exploiting it lead to compromise of the underlying instance or container. This allow an adversary a path to access the cloud or container APIs (e.g., via the Cloud Instance Metadata API), exploit container host access via Escape to Host, or take advantage of weak identity and access management policies. also exploit edge network infrastructure and related appliances, specifically targeting devices that do not support robust host-based defenses. For websites and databases, the OWASP top 10 and CWE top 25 highlight the most common web-based vulnerabilities.},\n",
       " 'T1558': {'name': 'Steal or Forge Kerberos Tickets',\n",
       "  'description': 'attempt to subvert Kerberos authentication by stealing or forging Kerberos tickets to enable Pass the Ticket. Kerberos is an authentication protocol widely used in modern Windows domain environments. In Kerberos environments, referred to as “realms”, there are three basic participants: client, service, and Key Distribution Center (KDC). Clients request access to a service and through the exchange of Kerberos tickets, originating from KDC, they are granted access after having successfully authenticated. The KDC is responsible for both authentication and ticket granting. attempt to abuse Kerberos by stealing tickets or forging tickets to enable unauthorized access. On Windows, the built-in klist utility be used to list and analyze cached Kerberos tickets.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['credential-access'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['kerberos',\n",
       "   'tickets',\n",
       "   'authentication',\n",
       "   'kdc',\n",
       "   'access',\n",
       "   'attempt',\n",
       "   'stealing',\n",
       "   'forging',\n",
       "   'enable',\n",
       "   'ticket'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': attempt to subvert Kerberos authentication by stealing or forging Kerberos tickets to enable Pass the Ticket. Kerberos is an authentication protocol widely used in modern Windows domain environments. In Kerberos environments, referred to as “realms”, there are three basic participants: client, service, and Key Distribution Center (KDC). Clients request access to a service and through the exchange of Kerberos tickets, originating from KDC, they are granted access after having successfully authenticated. The KDC is responsible for both authentication and ticket granting. attempt to abuse Kerberos by stealing tickets or forging tickets to enable unauthorized access. On Windows, the built-in klist utility be used to list and analyze cached Kerberos tickets.},\n",
       " 'T1555': {'name': 'Credentials from Password Stores',\n",
       "  'description': 'search for common password storage locations to obtain user credentials. Passwords are stored in several places on a system, depending on the operating system or application holding the credentials. There are also specific applications and services that store passwords to make them easier for users to manage and maintain, such as password managers and cloud secrets vaults. Once credentials are obtained, they be used to perform lateral movement and access restricted information.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['credential-access'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['credentials',\n",
       "   'password',\n",
       "   'passwords',\n",
       "   'system',\n",
       "   'search',\n",
       "   'common',\n",
       "   'storage',\n",
       "   'locations',\n",
       "   'obtain',\n",
       "   'user'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': search for common password storage locations to obtain user credentials. Passwords are stored in several places on a system, depending on the operating system or application holding the credentials. There are also specific applications and services that store passwords to make them easier for users to manage and maintain, such as password managers and cloud secrets vaults. Once credentials are obtained, they be used to perform lateral movement and access restricted information.},\n",
       " 'T1567': {'name': 'Exfiltration Over Web Service',\n",
       "  'description': 'use an existing, legitimate external Web service to exfiltrate data rather than their primary command and control channel. Popular Web services acting as an exfiltration mechanism give a significant amount of cover due to the likelihood that hosts within a network are already communicating with them prior to compromise. Firewall rules also already exist to permit traffic to these services. Web service providers also commonly use SSL/TLS encryption, giving an added level of protection.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['exfiltration'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['web',\n",
       "   'use',\n",
       "   'service',\n",
       "   'services',\n",
       "   'existing',\n",
       "   'legitimate',\n",
       "   'external',\n",
       "   'exfiltrate',\n",
       "   'data',\n",
       "   'primary'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': use an existing, legitimate external Web service to exfiltrate data rather than their primary command and control channel. Popular Web services acting as an exfiltration mechanism give a significant amount of cover due to the likelihood that hosts within a network are already communicating with them prior to compromise. Firewall rules also already exist to permit traffic to these services. Web service providers also commonly use SSL/TLS encryption, giving an added level of protection.},\n",
       " 'T1219': {'name': 'Remote Access Software',\n",
       "  'description': \"An adversary use legitimate desktop support and remote access software to establish an interactive command and control channel to target systems within networks. These services, such as VNC, Team Viewer, AnyDesk, ScreenConnect, LogMein, AmmyyAdmin, and other remote monitoring and management (RMM) tools, are commonly used as legitimate technical support software and be allowed by application control within a target environment. Remote access software be installed and used post-compromise as an alternate communications channel for redundant access or as a way to establish an interactive remote desktop session with the target system. They also be used as a component of malware to establish a reverse connection or back-connect to a service or adversary-controlled system. similarly abuse response features included in EDR and other defensive tools that enable remote access. Installation of many remote access software also include persistence (e.g., the software's installation routine creates a Windows Service). Remote access modules/features also exist as part of otherwise existing software (e.g., Google Chrome’s Remote Desktop).\",\n",
       "  'tactics': ['command-and-control'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['remote',\n",
       "   'access',\n",
       "   'software',\n",
       "   'desktop',\n",
       "   'establish',\n",
       "   'target',\n",
       "   'adversary',\n",
       "   'legitimate',\n",
       "   'support',\n",
       "   'interactive'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': An adversary use legitimate desktop support and remote access software to establish an interactive command and control channel to target systems within networks. These services, such as VNC, Team Viewer, AnyDesk, ScreenConnect, LogMein, AmmyyAdmin, and other remote monitoring and management (RMM) tools, are commonly used as legitimate technical support software and be allowed by application control within a target environment. Remote access software be installed and used post-compromise as an alternate communications channel for redundant access or as a way to establish an interactive remote desktop session with the target system. They also be used as a component of malware to establish a reverse connection or back-connect to a service or adversary-controlled system. similarly abuse response features included in EDR and other defensive tools that enable remote access. Installation of many remote access software also include persistence (e.g., the software's installation routine creates a Windows Service). Remote access modules/features also exist as part of otherwise existing software (e.g., Google Chrome’s Remote Desktop).},\n",
       " 'T1583.001': {'name': 'Domains',\n",
       "  'description': 'acquire domains that be used during targeting. Domain names are the human readable names used to represent one or more IP addresses. They be purchased or, in some cases, acquired for free. use acquired domains for a variety of purposes, including for Phishing, Drive-by Compromise, and Command and Control. choose domains that are similar to legitimate domains, including through use of homoglyphs or use of a different top-level domain (TLD). Typosquatting be used to aid in delivery of payloads via Drive-by Compromise. also use internationalized domain names (IDNs) and different character sets (e.g. Cyrillic, Greek, etc.) to execute \"IDN homograph attacks,\" creating visually similar lookalike domains used to deliver malware to victim machines. Different URIs/URLs also be dynamically generated to uniquely serve malicious content to victims (including one-time, single use domain names). also acquire and repurpose expired domains, which be potentially already allowlisted/trusted by defenders based on an existing reputation/history. Domain registrars each maintain a publicly viewable database that displays contact information for every registered domain. Private WHOIS services display alternative information, such as their own company data, rather than the owner of the domain. use such private WHOIS services to obscure information about who owns a purchased domain. further interrupt efforts to track their infrastructure by using varied registration information and purchasing domains with different domain registrars. In addition to legitimately purchasing a domain, an adversary register a new domain in a compromised environment. For example, in AWS environments, leverage the Route53 domain service to register a domain and create hosted zones pointing to resources of the threat actor’s choosing.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['resource-development'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['domain',\n",
       "   'domains',\n",
       "   'use',\n",
       "   'names',\n",
       "   'different',\n",
       "   'information',\n",
       "   'including',\n",
       "   'acquire',\n",
       "   'purchased',\n",
       "   'acquired'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': acquire domains that be used during targeting. Domain names are the human readable names used to represent one or more IP addresses. They be purchased or, in some cases, acquired for free. use acquired domains for a variety of purposes, including for Phishing, Drive-by Compromise, and Command and Control. choose domains that are similar to legitimate domains, including through use of homoglyphs or use of a different top-level domain (TLD). Typosquatting be used to aid in delivery of payloads via Drive-by Compromise. also use internationalized domain names (IDNs) and different character sets (e.g. Cyrillic, Greek, etc.) to execute \"IDN homograph attacks,\" creating visually similar lookalike domains used to deliver malware to victim machines. Different URIs/URLs also be dynamically generated to uniquely serve malicious content to victims (including one-time, single use domain names). also acquire and repurpose expired domains, which be potentially already allowlisted/trusted by defenders based on an existing reputation/history. Domain registrars each maintain a publicly viewable database that displays contact information for every registered domain. Private WHOIS services display alternative information, such as their own company data, rather than the owner of the domain. use such private WHOIS services to obscure information about who owns a purchased domain. further interrupt efforts to track their infrastructure by using varied registration information and purchasing domains with different domain registrars. In addition to legitimately purchasing a domain, an adversary register a new domain in a compromised environment. For example, in AWS environments, leverage the Route53 domain service to register a domain and create hosted zones pointing to resources of the threat actor’s choosing.},\n",
       " 'T1560.002': {'name': 'Archive via Library',\n",
       "  'description': 'An adversary compress or encrypt data that is collected prior to exfiltration using 3rd party libraries. Many libraries exist that archive data, including Python rarfile , libzip , and zlib . Most libraries include functionality to encrypt and/or compress data. Some archival libraries are preinstalled on systems, such as bzip2 on macOS and Linux, and zip on Windows. Note that the libraries are different from the utilities. The libraries be linked against when compiling, while the utilities require spawning a subshell, or a similar execution mechanism.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['collection'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['libraries',\n",
       "   'data',\n",
       "   'compress',\n",
       "   'encrypt',\n",
       "   'utilities',\n",
       "   'adversary',\n",
       "   'collected',\n",
       "   'prior',\n",
       "   'exfiltration',\n",
       "   'party'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': An adversary compress or encrypt data that is collected prior to exfiltration using 3rd party libraries. Many libraries exist that archive data, including Python rarfile , libzip , and zlib . Most libraries include functionality to encrypt and/or compress data. Some archival libraries are preinstalled on systems, such as bzip2 on macOS and Linux, and zip on Windows. Note that the libraries are different from the utilities. The libraries be linked against when compiling, while the utilities require spawning a subshell, or a similar execution mechanism.},\n",
       " 'T1055.003': {'name': 'Thread Execution Hijacking',\n",
       "  'description': \"inject malicious code into hijacked processes in order to evade process-based defenses as well as elevate privileges. Thread Execution Hijacking is a method of executing arbitrary code in the address space of a separate live process. Thread Execution Hijacking is commonly performed by suspending an existing process then unmapping/hollowing its memory, which then be replaced with malicious code or the path to a DLL. A handle to an existing victim process is first created with native Windows API calls such as OpenThread. At this point the process be suspended then written to, realigned to the injected code, and resumed via SuspendThread , VirtualAllocEx, WriteProcessMemory, SetThreadContext, then ResumeThread respectively. This is very similar to Process Hollowing but targets an existing process rather than creating a process in a suspended state. Running code in the context of another process allow access to the process's memory, system/network resources, and elevated privileges. Execution via Thread Execution Hijacking also evade detection from security products since the execution is masked under a legitimate process.\",\n",
       "  'tactics': ['defense-evasion', 'privilege-escalation'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['process',\n",
       "   'code',\n",
       "   'execution',\n",
       "   'thread',\n",
       "   'hijacking',\n",
       "   'existing',\n",
       "   'malicious',\n",
       "   'evade',\n",
       "   'privileges',\n",
       "   'hollowing'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': inject malicious code into hijacked processes in order to evade process-based defenses as well as elevate privileges. Thread Execution Hijacking is a method of executing arbitrary code in the address space of a separate live process. Thread Execution Hijacking is commonly performed by suspending an existing process then unmapping/hollowing its memory, which then be replaced with malicious code or the path to a DLL. A handle to an existing victim process is first created with native Windows API calls such as OpenThread. At this point the process be suspended then written to, realigned to the injected code, and resumed via SuspendThread , VirtualAllocEx, WriteProcessMemory, SetThreadContext, then ResumeThread respectively. This is very similar to Process Hollowing but targets an existing process rather than creating a process in a suspended state. Running code in the context of another process allow access to the process's memory, system/network resources, and elevated privileges. Execution via Thread Execution Hijacking also evade detection from security products since the execution is masked under a legitimate process.},\n",
       " 'T1079': {'name': 'Multilayer Encryption',\n",
       "  'description': 'An adversary performs C2 communications using multiple layers of encryption, typically (but not exclusively) tunneling a custom encryption scheme within a protocol encryption scheme such as HTTPS or SMTPS.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['command-and-control'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['encryption',\n",
       "   'scheme',\n",
       "   'adversary',\n",
       "   'performs',\n",
       "   'communications',\n",
       "   'multiple',\n",
       "   'layers',\n",
       "   'typically',\n",
       "   'exclusively',\n",
       "   'tunneling'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': An adversary performs C2 communications using multiple layers of encryption, typically (but not exclusively) tunneling a custom encryption scheme within a protocol encryption scheme such as HTTPS or SMTPS.},\n",
       " 'T1036': {'name': 'Masquerading',\n",
       "  'description': 'attempt to manipulate features of their artifacts to make them appear legitimate or benign to users and/or security tools. Masquerading occurs when the name or location of an object, legitimate or malicious, is manipulated or abused for the sake of evading defenses and observation. This include manipulating file metadata, tricking users into misidentifying the file type, and giving legitimate task or service names. Renaming abusable system utilities to evade security monitoring is also a form of Masquerading.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['defense-evasion'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['legitimate',\n",
       "   'users',\n",
       "   'security',\n",
       "   'masquerading',\n",
       "   'file',\n",
       "   'attempt',\n",
       "   'manipulate',\n",
       "   'features',\n",
       "   'artifacts',\n",
       "   'appear'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': attempt to manipulate features of their artifacts to make them appear legitimate or benign to users and/or security tools. Masquerading occurs when the name or location of an object, legitimate or malicious, is manipulated or abused for the sake of evading defenses and observation. This include manipulating file metadata, tricking users into misidentifying the file type, and giving legitimate task or service names. Renaming abusable system utilities to evade security monitoring is also a form of Masquerading.},\n",
       " 'T1546.011': {'name': 'Application Shimming',\n",
       "  'description': 'establish persistence and/or elevate privileges by executing malicious content triggered by application shims. The Microsoft Windows Application Compatibility Infrastructure/Framework (Application Shim) was created to allow for backward compatibility of software as the operating system codebase changes over time. For example, the application shimming feature allows developers to apply fixes to applications (without rewriting code) that were created for Windows XP so that it will work with Windows 10. Within the framework, shims are created to act as a buffer between the program (or more specifically, the Import Address Table) and the Windows OS. When a program is executed, the shim cache is referenced to determine if the program requires the use of the shim database (.sdb). If so, the shim database uses hooking to redirect the code as necessary in order to communicate with the OS. A list of all shims currently installed by the default Windows installer (sdbinst.exe) is kept in: * %WINDIR%\\\\AppPatch\\\\sysmain.sdb and * hklm\\\\software\\\\microsoft\\\\windows nt\\\\currentversion\\\\appcompatflags\\\\installedsdb Custom databases are stored in: * %WINDIR%\\\\AppPatch\\\\custom & %WINDIR%\\\\AppPatch\\\\AppPatch64\\\\Custom and * hklm\\\\software\\\\microsoft\\\\windows nt\\\\currentversion\\\\appcompatflags\\\\custom To keep shims secure, Windows designed them to run in user mode so they cannot modify the kernel and you must have administrator privileges to install a shim. However, certain shims be used to Bypass User Account Control (UAC and RedirectEXE), inject DLLs into processes (InjectDLL), disable Data Execution Prevention (DisableNX) and Structure Exception Handling (DisableSEH), and intercept memory addresses (GetProcAddress). Utilizing these shims allow an adversary to perform several malicious acts such as elevate privileges, install backdoors, disable defenses like Windows Defender, etc. Shims also be abused to establish persistence by continuously being invoked by affected programs.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['persistence', 'privilege-escalation'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['shims',\n",
       "   'windows',\n",
       "   'shim',\n",
       "   'application',\n",
       "   'privileges',\n",
       "   'created',\n",
       "   'program',\n",
       "   'establish',\n",
       "   'persistence',\n",
       "   'elevate'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': establish persistence and/or elevate privileges by executing malicious content triggered by application shims. The Microsoft Windows Application Compatibility Infrastructure/Framework (Application Shim) was created to allow for backward compatibility of software as the operating system codebase changes over time. For example, the application shimming feature allows developers to apply fixes to applications (without rewriting code) that were created for Windows XP so that it will work with Windows 10. Within the framework, shims are created to act as a buffer between the program (or more specifically, the Import Address Table) and the Windows OS. When a program is executed, the shim cache is referenced to determine if the program requires the use of the shim database (.sdb). If so, the shim database uses hooking to redirect the code as necessary in order to communicate with the OS. A list of all shims currently installed by the default Windows installer (sdbinst.exe) is kept in: * %WINDIR%\\AppPatch\\sysmain.sdb and * hklm\\software\\microsoft\\windows nt\\currentversion\\appcompatflags\\installedsdb Custom databases are stored in: * %WINDIR%\\AppPatch\\custom & %WINDIR%\\AppPatch\\AppPatch64\\Custom and * hklm\\software\\microsoft\\windows nt\\currentversion\\appcompatflags\\custom To keep shims secure, Windows designed them to run in user mode so they cannot modify the kernel and you must have administrator privileges to install a shim. However, certain shims be used to Bypass User Account Control (UAC and RedirectEXE), inject DLLs into processes (InjectDLL), disable Data Execution Prevention (DisableNX) and Structure Exception Handling (DisableSEH), and intercept memory addresses (GetProcAddress). Utilizing these shims allow an adversary to perform several malicious acts such as elevate privileges, install backdoors, disable defenses like Windows Defender, etc. Shims also be abused to establish persistence by continuously being invoked by affected programs.},\n",
       " 'T1552': {'name': 'Unsecured Credentials',\n",
       "  'description': 'search compromised systems to find and obtain insecurely stored credentials. These credentials be stored and/or misplaced in many locations on a system, including plaintext files (e.g. Bash History), operating system or application-specific repositories (e.g. Credentials in Registry), or other specialized files/artifacts (e.g. Private Keys).',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['credential-access'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['credentials',\n",
       "   'stored',\n",
       "   'system',\n",
       "   'files',\n",
       "   'search',\n",
       "   'compromised',\n",
       "   'systems',\n",
       "   'find',\n",
       "   'obtain',\n",
       "   'insecurely'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': search compromised systems to find and obtain insecurely stored credentials. These credentials be stored and/or misplaced in many locations on a system, including plaintext files (e.g. Bash History), operating system or application-specific repositories (e.g. Credentials in Registry), or other specialized files/artifacts (e.g. Private Keys).},\n",
       " 'T1547.010': {'name': 'Port Monitors',\n",
       "  'description': 'use port monitors to run an adversary supplied DLL during system boot for persistence or privilege escalation. A port monitor be set through the AddMonitor API call to set a DLL to be loaded at startup. This DLL be located in C:\\\\Windows\\\\System32 and will be loaded and run by the print spooler service, spoolsv.exe, under SYSTEM level permissions on boot. Alternatively, an arbitrary DLL be loaded if permissions allow writing a fully-qualified pathname for that DLL to the Driver value of an existing or new arbitrarily named subkey of HKLM\\\\SYSTEM\\\\CurrentControlSet\\\\Control\\\\Print\\\\Monitors. The Registry key contains entries for the following: * Local Port * Standard TCP/IP Port * USB Monitor * WSD Port',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['persistence', 'privilege-escalation'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['port',\n",
       "   'dll',\n",
       "   'loaded',\n",
       "   'run',\n",
       "   'system',\n",
       "   'boot',\n",
       "   'monitor',\n",
       "   'set',\n",
       "   'permissions',\n",
       "   'use'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': use port monitors to run an adversary supplied DLL during system boot for persistence or privilege escalation. A port monitor be set through the AddMonitor API call to set a DLL to be loaded at startup. This DLL be located in C:\\Windows\\System32 and will be loaded and run by the print spooler service, spoolsv.exe, under SYSTEM level permissions on boot. Alternatively, an arbitrary DLL be loaded if permissions allow writing a fully-qualified pathname for that DLL to the Driver value of an existing or new arbitrarily named subkey of HKLM\\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Control\\Print\\Monitors. The Registry key contains entries for the following: * Local Port * Standard TCP/IP Port * USB Monitor * WSD Port},\n",
       " 'T1070.008': {'name': 'Clear Mailbox Data',\n",
       "  'description': 'modify mail and mail application data to remove evidence of their activity. Email applications allow users and other programs to export and delete mailbox data via command line tools or use of APIs. Mail application data be emails, email metadata, or logs generated by the application or operating system, such as export requests. manipulate emails and mailbox data to remove logs, artifacts, and metadata, such as evidence of Phishing/Internal Spearphishing, Email Collection, Mail Protocols for command and control, or email-based exfiltration such as Exfiltration Over Alternative Protocol. For example, to remove evidence on Exchange servers have used the ExchangePowerShell PowerShell module, including Remove-MailboxExportRequest to remove evidence of mailbox exports. On Linux and macOS, also delete emails through a command line utility called mail or use AppleScript to interact with APIs on macOS. also remove emails and metadata/headers indicative of spam or suspicious activity (for example, through the use of organization-wide transport rules) to reduce the likelihood of malicious emails being detected by security products.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['defense-evasion'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['remove',\n",
       "   'mail',\n",
       "   'emails',\n",
       "   'data',\n",
       "   'evidence',\n",
       "   'email',\n",
       "   'application',\n",
       "   'mailbox',\n",
       "   'command',\n",
       "   'use'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': modify mail and mail application data to remove evidence of their activity. Email applications allow users and other programs to export and delete mailbox data via command line tools or use of APIs. Mail application data be emails, email metadata, or logs generated by the application or operating system, such as export requests. manipulate emails and mailbox data to remove logs, artifacts, and metadata, such as evidence of Phishing/Internal Spearphishing, Email Collection, Mail Protocols for command and control, or email-based exfiltration such as Exfiltration Over Alternative Protocol. For example, to remove evidence on Exchange servers have used the ExchangePowerShell PowerShell module, including Remove-MailboxExportRequest to remove evidence of mailbox exports. On Linux and macOS, also delete emails through a command line utility called mail or use AppleScript to interact with APIs on macOS. also remove emails and metadata/headers indicative of spam or suspicious activity (for example, through the use of organization-wide transport rules) to reduce the likelihood of malicious emails being detected by security products.},\n",
       " 'T1037.002': {'name': 'Login Hook',\n",
       "  'description': 'use a Login Hook to establish persistence executed upon user logon. A login hook is a plist file that points to a specific script to execute with root privileges upon user logon. The plist file is located in the /Library/Preferences/com.apple.loginwindow.plist file and be modified using the defaults command-line utility. This behavior is the same for logout hooks where a script be executed upon user logout. All hooks require administrator permissions to modify or create hooks. add or insert a path to a malicious script in the com.apple.loginwindow.plist file, using the LoginHook or LogoutHook key-value pair. The malicious script is executed upon the next user login. If a login hook already exists, add additional commands to an existing login hook. There be only one login and logout hook on a system at a time. **Note:** Login hooks were deprecated in 10.11 version of macOS in favor of Launch Daemon and Launch Agent',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['persistence', 'privilege-escalation'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['login',\n",
       "   'hook',\n",
       "   'user',\n",
       "   'file',\n",
       "   'script',\n",
       "   'hooks',\n",
       "   'executed',\n",
       "   'logout',\n",
       "   'logon',\n",
       "   'plist'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': use a Login Hook to establish persistence executed upon user logon. A login hook is a plist file that points to a specific script to execute with root privileges upon user logon. The plist file is located in the /Library/Preferences/com.apple.loginwindow.plist file and be modified using the defaults command-line utility. This behavior is the same for logout hooks where a script be executed upon user logout. All hooks require administrator permissions to modify or create hooks. add or insert a path to a malicious script in the com.apple.loginwindow.plist file, using the LoginHook or LogoutHook key-value pair. The malicious script is executed upon the next user login. If a login hook already exists, add additional commands to an existing login hook. There be only one login and logout hook on a system at a time. **Note:** Login hooks were deprecated in 10.11 version of macOS in favor of Launch Daemon and Launch Agent},\n",
       " 'T1659': {'name': 'Content Injection',\n",
       "  'description': 'gain access and continuously communicate with victims by injecting malicious content into systems through online network traffic. Rather than luring victims to malicious payloads hosted on a compromised website (i.e., Drive-by Target followed by Drive-by Compromise), initially access victims through compromised data-transfer channels where they manipulate traffic and/or inject their own content. These compromised online network channels also be used to deliver additional payloads (i.e., Ingress Tool Transfer) and other data to already compromised systems. inject content to victim systems in various ways, including: * From the middle, where the adversary is in-between legitimate online client-server communications (**Note:** this is similar but distinct from Adversary-in-the-Middle, which describes AiTM activity solely within an enterprise environment) * From the side, where malicious content is injected and races to the client as a fake response to requests of a legitimate online server Content injection is often the result of compromised upstream communication channels, for example at the level of an internet service provider (ISP) as is the case with \"lawful interception.\"',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['initial-access', 'command-and-control'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['content',\n",
       "   'compromised',\n",
       "   'online',\n",
       "   'victims',\n",
       "   'malicious',\n",
       "   'systems',\n",
       "   'channels',\n",
       "   'access',\n",
       "   'network',\n",
       "   'traffic'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': gain access and continuously communicate with victims by injecting malicious content into systems through online network traffic. Rather than luring victims to malicious payloads hosted on a compromised website (i.e., Drive-by Target followed by Drive-by Compromise), initially access victims through compromised data-transfer channels where they manipulate traffic and/or inject their own content. These compromised online network channels also be used to deliver additional payloads (i.e., Ingress Tool Transfer) and other data to already compromised systems. inject content to victim systems in various ways, including: * From the middle, where the adversary is in-between legitimate online client-server communications (**Note:** this is similar but distinct from Adversary-in-the-Middle, which describes AiTM activity solely within an enterprise environment) * From the side, where malicious content is injected and races to the client as a fake response to requests of a legitimate online server Content injection is often the result of compromised upstream communication channels, for example at the level of an internet service provider (ISP) as is the case with \"lawful interception.\"},\n",
       " 'T1055': {'name': 'Process Injection',\n",
       "  'description': \"inject code into processes in order to evade process-based defenses as well as elevate privileges. Process injection is a method of executing arbitrary code in the address space of a separate live process. Running code in the context of another process allow access to the process's memory, system/network resources, and elevated privileges. Execution via process injection also evade detection from security products since the execution is masked under a legitimate process. There are many different ways to inject code into a process, many of which abuse legitimate functionalities. These implementations exist for every major OS but are typically platform specific. More sophisticated samples perform multiple process injections to segment modules and further evade detection, utilizing named pipes or other inter-process communication (IPC) mechanisms as a communication channel.\",\n",
       "  'tactics': ['defense-evasion', 'privilege-escalation'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['process',\n",
       "   'code',\n",
       "   'evade',\n",
       "   'inject',\n",
       "   'privileges',\n",
       "   'injection',\n",
       "   'execution',\n",
       "   'detection',\n",
       "   'legitimate',\n",
       "   'communication'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': inject code into processes in order to evade process-based defenses as well as elevate privileges. Process injection is a method of executing arbitrary code in the address space of a separate live process. Running code in the context of another process allow access to the process's memory, system/network resources, and elevated privileges. Execution via process injection also evade detection from security products since the execution is masked under a legitimate process. There are many different ways to inject code into a process, many of which abuse legitimate functionalities. These implementations exist for every major OS but are typically platform specific. More sophisticated samples perform multiple process injections to segment modules and further evade detection, utilizing named pipes or other inter-process communication (IPC) mechanisms as a communication channel.},\n",
       " 'T1567.004': {'name': 'Exfiltration Over Webhook',\n",
       "  'description': 'exfiltrate data to a webhook endpoint rather than over their primary command and control channel. Webhooks are simple mechanisms for allowing a server to push data over HTTP/S to a client without the need for the client to continuously poll the server. Many public and commercial services, such as Discord, Slack, and webhook.site, support the creation of webhook endpoints that be used by other services, such as Github, Jira, or Trello. When changes happen in the linked services (such as pushing a repository update or modifying a ticket), these services will automatically post the data to the webhook endpoint for use by the consuming application. link an adversary-owned environment to a victim-owned SaaS service to achieve repeated Automated Exfiltration of emails, chat messages, and other data. Alternatively, instead of linking the webhook endpoint to a service, an adversary manually post staged data directly to the URL in order to exfiltrate it. Access to webhook endpoints is often over HTTPS, which gives the adversary an additional level of protection. Exfiltration leveraging webhooks also blend in with normal network traffic if the webhook endpoint points to a commonly used SaaS application or collaboration service.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['exfiltration'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['webhook',\n",
       "   'data',\n",
       "   'endpoint',\n",
       "   'services',\n",
       "   'adversary',\n",
       "   'service',\n",
       "   'exfiltrate',\n",
       "   'webhooks',\n",
       "   'server',\n",
       "   'client'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': exfiltrate data to a webhook endpoint rather than over their primary command and control channel. Webhooks are simple mechanisms for allowing a server to push data over HTTP/S to a client without the need for the client to continuously poll the server. Many public and commercial services, such as Discord, Slack, and webhook.site, support the creation of webhook endpoints that be used by other services, such as Github, Jira, or Trello. When changes happen in the linked services (such as pushing a repository update or modifying a ticket), these services will automatically post the data to the webhook endpoint for use by the consuming application. link an adversary-owned environment to a victim-owned SaaS service to achieve repeated Automated Exfiltration of emails, chat messages, and other data. Alternatively, instead of linking the webhook endpoint to a service, an adversary manually post staged data directly to the URL in order to exfiltrate it. Access to webhook endpoints is often over HTTPS, which gives the adversary an additional level of protection. Exfiltration leveraging webhooks also blend in with normal network traffic if the webhook endpoint points to a commonly used SaaS application or collaboration service.},\n",
       " 'T1139': {'name': 'Bash History',\n",
       "  'description': 'Bash keeps track of the commands users type on the command-line with the \"history\" utility. Once a user logs out, the history is flushed to the user’s .bash_history file. For each user, this file resides at the same location: ~/.bash_history. Typically, this file keeps track of the user’s last 500 commands. Users often type usernames and passwords on the command-line as parameters to programs, which then get saved to this file when they log out. Attackers abuse this by looking through the file for potential credentials.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['credential-access'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['file',\n",
       "   'user',\n",
       "   'keeps',\n",
       "   'track',\n",
       "   'commands',\n",
       "   'users',\n",
       "   'type',\n",
       "   'command',\n",
       "   'line',\n",
       "   'history'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': Bash keeps track of the commands users type on the command-line with the \"history\" utility. Once a user logs out, the history is flushed to the user’s .bash_history file. For each user, this file resides at the same location: ~/.bash_history. Typically, this file keeps track of the user’s last 500 commands. Users often type usernames and passwords on the command-line as parameters to programs, which then get saved to this file when they log out. Attackers abuse this by looking through the file for potential credentials.},\n",
       " 'T1205': {'name': 'Traffic Signaling',\n",
       "  'description': 'use traffic signaling to hide open ports or other malicious functionality used for persistence or command and control. Traffic signaling involves the use of a magic value or sequence that must be sent to a system to trigger a special response, such as opening a closed port or executing a malicious task. This take the form of sending a series of packets with certain characteristics before a port will be opened that the adversary use for command and control. Usually this series of packets consists of attempted connections to a predefined sequence of closed ports (i.e. Port Knocking), but involve unusual flags, specific strings, or other unique characteristics. After the sequence is completed, opening a port be accomplished by the host-based firewall, but also be implemented by custom software. also communicate with an already open port, but the service listening on that port will only respond to commands or trigger other malicious functionality if passed the appropriate magic value(s). The observation of the signal packets to trigger the communication be conducted through different methods. One means, originally implemented by Cd00r , is to use the libpcap libraries to sniff for the packets in question. Another method leverages raw sockets, which enables the malware to use ports that are already open for use by other programs. On network devices, use crafted packets to enable Network Device Authentication for standard services offered by the device such as telnet. Such signaling also be used to open a closed service port such as telnet, or to trigger module modification of malware implants on the device, adding, removing, or changing malicious capabilities. use crafted packets to attempt to connect to one or more (open or closed) ports, but also attempt to connect to a router interface, broadcast, and network address IP on the same port in order to achieve their goals and objectives. To enable this traffic signaling on embedded devices, must first achieve and leverage Patch System Image due to the monolithic nature of the architecture. also use the Wake-on-LAN feature to turn on powered off systems. Wake-on-LAN is a hardware feature that allows a powered down system to be powered on, or woken up, by sending a magic packet to it. Once the system is powered on, it become a target for lateral movement.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['persistence', 'command-and-control', 'defense-evasion'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['use',\n",
       "   'port',\n",
       "   'packets',\n",
       "   'open',\n",
       "   'signaling',\n",
       "   'ports',\n",
       "   'malicious',\n",
       "   'system',\n",
       "   'trigger',\n",
       "   'closed'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': use traffic signaling to hide open ports or other malicious functionality used for persistence or command and control. Traffic signaling involves the use of a magic value or sequence that must be sent to a system to trigger a special response, such as opening a closed port or executing a malicious task. This take the form of sending a series of packets with certain characteristics before a port will be opened that the adversary use for command and control. Usually this series of packets consists of attempted connections to a predefined sequence of closed ports (i.e. Port Knocking), but involve unusual flags, specific strings, or other unique characteristics. After the sequence is completed, opening a port be accomplished by the host-based firewall, but also be implemented by custom software. also communicate with an already open port, but the service listening on that port will only respond to commands or trigger other malicious functionality if passed the appropriate magic value(s). The observation of the signal packets to trigger the communication be conducted through different methods. One means, originally implemented by Cd00r , is to use the libpcap libraries to sniff for the packets in question. Another method leverages raw sockets, which enables the malware to use ports that are already open for use by other programs. On network devices, use crafted packets to enable Network Device Authentication for standard services offered by the device such as telnet. Such signaling also be used to open a closed service port such as telnet, or to trigger module modification of malware implants on the device, adding, removing, or changing malicious capabilities. use crafted packets to attempt to connect to one or more (open or closed) ports, but also attempt to connect to a router interface, broadcast, and network address IP on the same port in order to achieve their goals and objectives. To enable this traffic signaling on embedded devices, must first achieve and leverage Patch System Image due to the monolithic nature of the architecture. also use the Wake-on-LAN feature to turn on powered off systems. Wake-on-LAN is a hardware feature that allows a powered down system to be powered on, or woken up, by sending a magic packet to it. Once the system is powered on, it become a target for lateral movement.},\n",
       " 'T1021.008': {'name': 'Direct Cloud VM Connections',\n",
       "  'description': 'leverage Valid Accounts to log directly into accessible cloud hosted compute infrastructure through cloud native methods. Many cloud providers offer interactive connections to virtual infrastructure that be accessed through the Cloud API, such as Azure Serial Console, AWS EC2 Instance Connect, and AWS System Manager.. Methods of authentication for these connections include passwords, application access tokens, or SSH keys. These cloud native methods , by default, allow for privileged access on the host with SYSTEM or root level access. utilize these cloud native methods to directly access virtual infrastructure and pivot through an environment. These connections typically provide direct console access to the VM rather than the execution of scripts (i.e., Cloud Administration Command).',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['lateral-movement'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['cloud',\n",
       "   'access',\n",
       "   'methods',\n",
       "   'infrastructure',\n",
       "   'native',\n",
       "   'connections',\n",
       "   'directly',\n",
       "   'virtual',\n",
       "   'console',\n",
       "   'aws'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': leverage Valid Accounts to log directly into accessible cloud hosted compute infrastructure through cloud native methods. Many cloud providers offer interactive connections to virtual infrastructure that be accessed through the Cloud API, such as Azure Serial Console, AWS EC2 Instance Connect, and AWS System Manager.. Methods of authentication for these connections include passwords, application access tokens, or SSH keys. These cloud native methods , by default, allow for privileged access on the host with SYSTEM or root level access. utilize these cloud native methods to directly access virtual infrastructure and pivot through an environment. These connections typically provide direct console access to the VM rather than the execution of scripts (i.e., Cloud Administration Command).},\n",
       " 'T1503': {'name': 'Credentials from Web Browsers',\n",
       "  'description': \"acquire credentials from web browsers by reading files specific to the target browser. Web browsers commonly save credentials such as website usernames and passwords so that they do not need to be entered manually in the future. Web browsers typically store the credentials in an encrypted format within a credential store; however, methods exist to extract plaintext credentials from web browsers. For example, on Windows systems, encrypted credentials be obtained from Google Chrome by reading a database file, AppData\\\\Local\\\\Google\\\\Chrome\\\\User Data\\\\Default\\\\Login Data and executing a SQL query: SELECT action_url, username_value, password_value FROM logins;. The plaintext password then be obtained by passing the encrypted credentials to the Windows API function CryptUnprotectData, which uses the victim’s cached logon credentials as the decryption key. have executed similar procedures for common web browsers such as FireFox, Safari, Edge, etc. also acquire credentials by searching web browser process memory for patterns that commonly match credentials. After acquiring credentials from web browsers, attempt to recycle the credentials across different systems and/or accounts in order to expand access. This result in significantly furthering an adversary's objective in cases where credentials gained from web browsers overlap with privileged accounts (e.g. domain administrator).\",\n",
       "  'tactics': ['credential-access'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['credentials',\n",
       "   'web',\n",
       "   'browsers',\n",
       "   'encrypted',\n",
       "   'acquire',\n",
       "   'reading',\n",
       "   'browser',\n",
       "   'commonly',\n",
       "   'store',\n",
       "   'plaintext'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': acquire credentials from web browsers by reading files specific to the target browser. Web browsers commonly save credentials such as website usernames and passwords so that they do not need to be entered manually in the future. Web browsers typically store the credentials in an encrypted format within a credential store; however, methods exist to extract plaintext credentials from web browsers. For example, on Windows systems, encrypted credentials be obtained from Google Chrome by reading a database file, AppData\\Local\\Google\\Chrome\\User Data\\Default\\Login Data and executing a SQL query: SELECT action_url, username_value, password_value FROM logins;. The plaintext password then be obtained by passing the encrypted credentials to the Windows API function CryptUnprotectData, which uses the victim’s cached logon credentials as the decryption key. have executed similar procedures for common web browsers such as FireFox, Safari, Edge, etc. also acquire credentials by searching web browser process memory for patterns that commonly match credentials. After acquiring credentials from web browsers, attempt to recycle the credentials across different systems and/or accounts in order to expand access. This result in significantly furthering an adversary's objective in cases where credentials gained from web browsers overlap with privileged accounts (e.g. domain administrator).},\n",
       " 'T1218': {'name': 'System Binary Proxy Execution',\n",
       "  'description': 'bypass process and/or signature-based defenses by proxying execution of malicious content with signed, or otherwise trusted, binaries. Binaries used in this technique are often Microsoft-signed files, indicating that they have been either downloaded from Microsoft or are already native in the operating system. Binaries signed with trusted digital certificates typically execute on Windows systems protected by digital signature validation. Several Microsoft signed binaries that are default on Windows installations be used to proxy execution of other files or commands. Similarly, on Linux systems abuse trusted binaries such as split to proxy execution of malicious commands.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['defense-evasion'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['binaries',\n",
       "   'signed',\n",
       "   'execution',\n",
       "   'trusted',\n",
       "   'microsoft',\n",
       "   'signature',\n",
       "   'malicious',\n",
       "   'files',\n",
       "   'digital',\n",
       "   'windows'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': bypass process and/or signature-based defenses by proxying execution of malicious content with signed, or otherwise trusted, binaries. Binaries used in this technique are often Microsoft-signed files, indicating that they have been either downloaded from Microsoft or are already native in the operating system. Binaries signed with trusted digital certificates typically execute on Windows systems protected by digital signature validation. Several Microsoft signed binaries that are default on Windows installations be used to proxy execution of other files or commands. Similarly, on Linux systems abuse trusted binaries such as split to proxy execution of malicious commands.},\n",
       " 'T1153': {'name': 'Source',\n",
       "  'description': '**This technique has been deprecated and should no longer be used.** The source command loads functions into the current shell or executes files in the current context. This built-in command be run in two different ways source /path/to/filename [arguments] or .**This technique has been deprecated and should no longer be used.** /path/to/filename [arguments]. Take note of the space after the \".\". Without a space, a new shell is created that runs the program instead of running the program within the current context. This is often used to make certain features or functions available to a shell or to update a specific shell\\'s environment. abuse this functionality to execute programs. The file executed with this technique does not need to be marked executable beforehand.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['execution'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['shell',\n",
       "   'technique',\n",
       "   'current',\n",
       "   'deprecated',\n",
       "   'longer',\n",
       "   'source',\n",
       "   'command',\n",
       "   'functions',\n",
       "   'context',\n",
       "   'filename'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': **This technique has been deprecated and should no longer be used.** The source command loads functions into the current shell or executes files in the current context. This built-in command be run in two different ways source /path/to/filename [arguments] or .**This technique has been deprecated and should no longer be used.** /path/to/filename [arguments]. Take note of the space after the \".\". Without a space, a new shell is created that runs the program instead of running the program within the current context. This is often used to make certain features or functions available to a shell or to update a specific shell's environment. abuse this functionality to execute programs. The file executed with this technique does not need to be marked executable beforehand.},\n",
       " 'T1038': {'name': 'DLL Search Order Hijacking',\n",
       "  'description': 'Windows systems use a common method to look for required DLLs to load into a program. take advantage of the Windows DLL search order and programs that ambiguously specify DLLs to gain privilege escalation and persistence. perform DLL preloading, also called binary planting attacks, by placing a malicious DLL with the same name as an ambiguously specified DLL in a location that Windows searches before the legitimate DLL. Often this location is the current working directory of the program. Remote DLL preloading attacks occur when a program sets its current directory to a remote location such as a Web share before loading a DLL. use this behavior to cause the program to load a malicious DLL. also directly modify the way a program loads DLLs by replacing an existing DLL or modifying a .manifest or .local redirection file, directory, or junction to cause the program to load a different DLL to maintain persistence or privilege escalation. If a search order-vulnerable program is configured to run at a higher privilege level, then the adversary-controlled DLL that is loaded will also be executed at the higher level. In this case, the technique be used for privilege escalation from user to administrator or SYSTEM or from administrator to SYSTEM, depending on the program. Programs that fall victim to path hijacking appear to behave normally because malicious DLLs be configured to also load the legitimate DLLs they were meant to replace.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['persistence', 'defense-evasion', 'privilege-escalation'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['dll',\n",
       "   'program',\n",
       "   'dlls',\n",
       "   'load',\n",
       "   'privilege',\n",
       "   'windows',\n",
       "   'escalation',\n",
       "   'malicious',\n",
       "   'location',\n",
       "   'directory'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': Windows systems use a common method to look for required DLLs to load into a program. take advantage of the Windows DLL search order and programs that ambiguously specify DLLs to gain privilege escalation and persistence. perform DLL preloading, also called binary planting attacks, by placing a malicious DLL with the same name as an ambiguously specified DLL in a location that Windows searches before the legitimate DLL. Often this location is the current working directory of the program. Remote DLL preloading attacks occur when a program sets its current directory to a remote location such as a Web share before loading a DLL. use this behavior to cause the program to load a malicious DLL. also directly modify the way a program loads DLLs by replacing an existing DLL or modifying a .manifest or .local redirection file, directory, or junction to cause the program to load a different DLL to maintain persistence or privilege escalation. If a search order-vulnerable program is configured to run at a higher privilege level, then the adversary-controlled DLL that is loaded will also be executed at the higher level. In this case, the technique be used for privilege escalation from user to administrator or SYSTEM or from administrator to SYSTEM, depending on the program. Programs that fall victim to path hijacking appear to behave normally because malicious DLLs be configured to also load the legitimate DLLs they were meant to replace.},\n",
       " 'T1050': {'name': 'New Service',\n",
       "  'description': \"When operating systems boot up, they start programs or applications called services that perform background system functions. A service's configuration information, including the file path to the service's executable, is stored in the Windows Registry. install a new service that be configured to execute at startup by using utilities to interact with services or by directly modifying the Registry. The service name be disguised by using a name from a related operating system or benign software with Masquerading. Services be created with administrator privileges but are executed under SYSTEM privileges, so an adversary also use a service to escalate privileges from administrator to SYSTEM. also directly start services through Service Execution.\",\n",
       "  'tactics': ['persistence', 'privilege-escalation'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['service',\n",
       "   'services',\n",
       "   'system',\n",
       "   'privileges',\n",
       "   'operating',\n",
       "   'start',\n",
       "   'registry',\n",
       "   'directly',\n",
       "   'administrator',\n",
       "   'systems'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': When operating systems boot up, they start programs or applications called services that perform background system functions. A service's configuration information, including the file path to the service's executable, is stored in the Windows Registry. install a new service that be configured to execute at startup by using utilities to interact with services or by directly modifying the Registry. The service name be disguised by using a name from a related operating system or benign software with Masquerading. Services be created with administrator privileges but are executed under SYSTEM privileges, so an adversary also use a service to escalate privileges from administrator to SYSTEM. also directly start services through Service Execution.},\n",
       " 'T1070.006': {'name': 'Timestomp',\n",
       "  'description': 'modify file time attributes to hide new files or changes to existing files. Timestomping is a technique that modifies the timestamps of a file (the modify, access, create, and change times), often to mimic files that are in the same folder and blend malicious files with legitimate files. Both the $STANDARD_INFORMATION ($SI) and $FILE_NAME ($FN) attributes record times in a Master File Table (MFT) file. $SI (dates/time stamps) is displayed to the end user, including in the File System view, while $FN is dealt with by the kernel. Modifying the $SI attribute is the most common method of timestomping because it be modified at the user level using API calls. $FN timestomping, however, typically requires interacting with the system kernel or moving or renaming a file. modify timestamps on files so that they do not appear conspicuous to forensic investigators or file analysis tools. In order to evade detections that rely on identifying discrepancies between the $SI and $FN attributes, also engage in “double timestomping” by modifying times on both attributes simultaneously. Timestomping be used along with file name Masquerading to hide malware and tools.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['defense-evasion'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['file',\n",
       "   'files',\n",
       "   'timestomping',\n",
       "   'attributes',\n",
       "   'modify',\n",
       "   'times',\n",
       "   'time',\n",
       "   'hide',\n",
       "   'timestamps',\n",
       "   'user'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': modify file time attributes to hide new files or changes to existing files. Timestomping is a technique that modifies the timestamps of a file (the modify, access, create, and change times), often to mimic files that are in the same folder and blend malicious files with legitimate files. Both the $STANDARD_INFORMATION ($SI) and $FILE_NAME ($FN) attributes record times in a Master File Table (MFT) file. $SI (dates/time stamps) is displayed to the end user, including in the File System view, while $FN is dealt with by the kernel. Modifying the $SI attribute is the most common method of timestomping because it be modified at the user level using API calls. $FN timestomping, however, typically requires interacting with the system kernel or moving or renaming a file. modify timestamps on files so that they do not appear conspicuous to forensic investigators or file analysis tools. In order to evade detections that rely on identifying discrepancies between the $SI and $FN attributes, also engage in “double timestomping” by modifying times on both attributes simultaneously. Timestomping be used along with file name Masquerading to hide malware and tools.},\n",
       " 'T1557.004': {'name': 'Evil Twin',\n",
       "  'description': 'host seemingly genuine Wi-Fi access points to deceive users into connecting to malicious networks as a way of supporting follow-on behaviors such as Network Sniffing, Transmitted Data Manipulation, or Input Capture. By using a Service Set Identifier (SSID) of a legitimate Wi-Fi network, fraudulent Wi-Fi access points trick devices or users into connecting to malicious Wi-Fi networks. provide a stronger signal strength or block access to Wi-Fi access points to coerce or entice victim devices into connecting to malicious networks. A Wi-Fi Pineapple – a network security auditing and penetration testing tool – be deployed in Evil Twin attacks for ease of use and broader range. Custom certificates be used in an attempt to intercept HTTPS traffic. Similarly, also listen for client devices sending probe requests for known or previously connected networks (Preferred Network Lists or PNLs). When a malicious access point receives a probe request, respond with the same SSID to imitate the trusted, known network. Victim devices are led to believe the responding access point is from their PNL and initiate a connection to the fraudulent network. Upon logging into the malicious Wi-Fi access point, a user be directed to a fake login page or captive portal webpage to capture the victim’s credentials. Once a user is logged into the fraudulent Wi-Fi network, the adversary able to monitor network activity, manipulate data, or steal additional credentials. Locations with high concentrations of public Wi-Fi access, such as airports, coffee shops, or libraries, be targets for to set up illegitimate Wi-Fi access points.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['collection', 'credential-access'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['access',\n",
       "   'network',\n",
       "   'malicious',\n",
       "   'points',\n",
       "   'networks',\n",
       "   'devices',\n",
       "   'connecting',\n",
       "   'fraudulent',\n",
       "   'victim',\n",
       "   'point'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': host seemingly genuine Wi-Fi access points to deceive users into connecting to malicious networks as a way of supporting follow-on behaviors such as Network Sniffing, Transmitted Data Manipulation, or Input Capture. By using a Service Set Identifier (SSID) of a legitimate Wi-Fi network, fraudulent Wi-Fi access points trick devices or users into connecting to malicious Wi-Fi networks. provide a stronger signal strength or block access to Wi-Fi access points to coerce or entice victim devices into connecting to malicious networks. A Wi-Fi Pineapple – a network security auditing and penetration testing tool – be deployed in Evil Twin attacks for ease of use and broader range. Custom certificates be used in an attempt to intercept HTTPS traffic. Similarly, also listen for client devices sending probe requests for known or previously connected networks (Preferred Network Lists or PNLs). When a malicious access point receives a probe request, respond with the same SSID to imitate the trusted, known network. Victim devices are led to believe the responding access point is from their PNL and initiate a connection to the fraudulent network. Upon logging into the malicious Wi-Fi access point, a user be directed to a fake login page or captive portal webpage to capture the victim’s credentials. Once a user is logged into the fraudulent Wi-Fi network, the adversary able to monitor network activity, manipulate data, or steal additional credentials. Locations with high concentrations of public Wi-Fi access, such as airports, coffee shops, or libraries, be targets for to set up illegitimate Wi-Fi access points.},\n",
       " 'T1620': {'name': 'Reflective Code Loading',\n",
       "  'description': 'reflectively load code into a process in order to conceal the execution of malicious payloads. Reflective loading involves allocating then executing payloads directly within the memory of the process, vice creating a thread or process backed by a file path on disk (e.g., Shared Modules). Reflectively loaded payloads be compiled binaries, anonymous files (only present in RAM), or just snubs of fileless executable code (ex: position-independent shellcode). For example, the Assembly.Load() method executed by PowerShell be abused to load raw code into the running process. Reflective code injection is very similar to Process Injection except that the “injection” loads code into the processes’ own memory instead of that of a separate process. Reflective loading evade process-based detections since the execution of the arbitrary code be masked within a legitimate or otherwise benign process. Reflectively loading payloads directly into memory also avoid creating files or other artifacts on disk, while also enabling malware to keep these payloads encrypted (or otherwise obfuscated) until execution.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['defense-evasion'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['process',\n",
       "   'code',\n",
       "   'payloads',\n",
       "   'reflectively',\n",
       "   'load',\n",
       "   'execution',\n",
       "   'reflective',\n",
       "   'loading',\n",
       "   'memory',\n",
       "   'injection'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': reflectively load code into a process in order to conceal the execution of malicious payloads. Reflective loading involves allocating then executing payloads directly within the memory of the process, vice creating a thread or process backed by a file path on disk (e.g., Shared Modules). Reflectively loaded payloads be compiled binaries, anonymous files (only present in RAM), or just snubs of fileless executable code (ex: position-independent shellcode). For example, the Assembly.Load() method executed by PowerShell be abused to load raw code into the running process. Reflective code injection is very similar to Process Injection except that the “injection” loads code into the processes’ own memory instead of that of a separate process. Reflective loading evade process-based detections since the execution of the arbitrary code be masked within a legitimate or otherwise benign process. Reflectively loading payloads directly into memory also avoid creating files or other artifacts on disk, while also enabling malware to keep these payloads encrypted (or otherwise obfuscated) until execution.},\n",
       " 'T1016.002': {'name': 'Wi-Fi Discovery',\n",
       "  'description': 'search for information about Wi-Fi networks, such as network names and passwords, on compromised systems. use Wi-Fi information as part of Account Discovery, Remote System Discovery, and other discovery or Credential Access activity to support both ongoing and future campaigns. collect various types of information about Wi-Fi networks from hosts. For example, on Windows names and passwords of all Wi-Fi networks a device has previously connected to be available through netsh wlan show profiles to enumerate Wi-Fi names and then netsh wlan show profile “Wi-Fi name” key=clear to show a Wi-Fi network’s corresponding password. Additionally, names and other details of locally reachable Wi-Fi networks be discovered using calls to wlanAPI.dll Native API functions. On Linux, names and passwords of all Wi-Fi-networks a device has previously connected to be available in files under /etc/NetworkManager/system-connections/. On macOS, the password of a known Wi-Fi be identified with security find-generic-password -wa wifiname (requires admin username/password).',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['discovery'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['networks',\n",
       "   'names',\n",
       "   'password',\n",
       "   'information',\n",
       "   'passwords',\n",
       "   'discovery',\n",
       "   'network',\n",
       "   'system',\n",
       "   'device',\n",
       "   'previously'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': search for information about Wi-Fi networks, such as network names and passwords, on compromised systems. use Wi-Fi information as part of Account Discovery, Remote System Discovery, and other discovery or Credential Access activity to support both ongoing and future campaigns. collect various types of information about Wi-Fi networks from hosts. For example, on Windows names and passwords of all Wi-Fi networks a device has previously connected to be available through netsh wlan show profiles to enumerate Wi-Fi names and then netsh wlan show profile “Wi-Fi name” key=clear to show a Wi-Fi network’s corresponding password. Additionally, names and other details of locally reachable Wi-Fi networks be discovered using calls to wlanAPI.dll Native API functions. On Linux, names and passwords of all Wi-Fi-networks a device has previously connected to be available in files under /etc/NetworkManager/system-connections/. On macOS, the password of a known Wi-Fi be identified with security find-generic-password -wa wifiname (requires admin username/password).},\n",
       " 'T1480.002': {'name': 'Mutual Exclusion',\n",
       "  'description': 'constrain execution or actions based on the presence of a mutex associated with malware. A mutex is a locking mechanism used to synchronize access to a resource. Only one thread or process acquire a mutex at a given time. While local mutexes only exist within a given process, allowing multiple threads to synchronize access to a resource, system mutexes be used to synchronize the activities of multiple processes. By creating a unique system mutex associated with a particular malware, verify whether or not a system has already been compromised. In Linux environments, malware instead attempt to acquire a lock on a mutex file. If the malware is able to acquire the lock, it continues to execute; if it fails, it exits to avoid creating a second instance of itself. Mutex names be hard-coded or dynamically generated using a predictable algorithm.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['defense-evasion'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['mutex',\n",
       "   'malware',\n",
       "   'synchronize',\n",
       "   'acquire',\n",
       "   'system',\n",
       "   'associated',\n",
       "   'access',\n",
       "   'resource',\n",
       "   'process',\n",
       "   'given'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': constrain execution or actions based on the presence of a mutex associated with malware. A mutex is a locking mechanism used to synchronize access to a resource. Only one thread or process acquire a mutex at a given time. While local mutexes only exist within a given process, allowing multiple threads to synchronize access to a resource, system mutexes be used to synchronize the activities of multiple processes. By creating a unique system mutex associated with a particular malware, verify whether or not a system has already been compromised. In Linux environments, malware instead attempt to acquire a lock on a mutex file. If the malware is able to acquire the lock, it continues to execute; if it fails, it exits to avoid creating a second instance of itself. Mutex names be hard-coded or dynamically generated using a predictable algorithm.},\n",
       " 'T1564.011': {'name': 'Ignore Process Interrupts',\n",
       "  'description': 'evade defensive mechanisms by executing commands that hide from process interrupt signals. Many operating systems use signals to deliver messages to control process behavior. Command interpreters often include specific commands/flags that ignore errors and other hangups, such as when the user of the active session logs off. These interrupt signals also be used by defensive tools and/or analysts to pause or terminate specified running processes. invoke processes using nohup, PowerShell -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue, or similar commands that be immune to hangups. This enable malicious commands and malware to continue execution through system events that would otherwise terminate its execution, such as users logging off or the termination of its C2 network connection. Hiding from process interrupt signals allow malware to continue execution, but unlike Trap this does not establish Persistence since the process will not be re-invoked once actually terminated.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['defense-evasion'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['commands',\n",
       "   'process',\n",
       "   'signals',\n",
       "   'interrupt',\n",
       "   'execution',\n",
       "   'defensive',\n",
       "   'hangups',\n",
       "   'terminate',\n",
       "   'processes',\n",
       "   'malware'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': evade defensive mechanisms by executing commands that hide from process interrupt signals. Many operating systems use signals to deliver messages to control process behavior. Command interpreters often include specific commands/flags that ignore errors and other hangups, such as when the user of the active session logs off. These interrupt signals also be used by defensive tools and/or analysts to pause or terminate specified running processes. invoke processes using nohup, PowerShell -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue, or similar commands that be immune to hangups. This enable malicious commands and malware to continue execution through system events that would otherwise terminate its execution, such as users logging off or the termination of its C2 network connection. Hiding from process interrupt signals allow malware to continue execution, but unlike Trap this does not establish Persistence since the process will not be re-invoked once actually terminated.},\n",
       " 'T1611': {'name': 'Escape to Host',\n",
       "  'description': 'break out of a container to gain access to the underlying host. This allow an adversary access to other containerized resources from the host level or to the host itself. In principle, containerized resources should provide a clear separation of application functionality and be isolated from the host environment. There are multiple ways an adversary escape to a host environment. Examples include creating a container configured to mount the host’s filesystem using the bind parameter, which allows the adversary to drop payloads and execute control utilities such as cron on the host; utilizing a privileged container to run commands or load a malicious kernel module on the underlying host; or abusing system calls such as unshare and keyctl to escalate privileges and steal secrets. Additionally, an adversary be able to exploit a compromised container with a mounted container management socket, such as docker.sock, to break out of the container via a Container Administration Command. also escape via Exploitation for Privilege Escalation, such as exploiting vulnerabilities in global symbolic links in order to access the root directory of a host machine. Gaining access to the host provide the adversary with the opportunity to achieve follow-on objectives, such as establishing persistence, moving laterally within the environment, accessing other containers running on the host, or setting up a command and control channel on the host.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['privilege-escalation'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['host',\n",
       "   'container',\n",
       "   'adversary',\n",
       "   'access',\n",
       "   'environment',\n",
       "   'break',\n",
       "   'underlying',\n",
       "   'containerized',\n",
       "   'resources',\n",
       "   'provide'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': break out of a container to gain access to the underlying host. This allow an adversary access to other containerized resources from the host level or to the host itself. In principle, containerized resources should provide a clear separation of application functionality and be isolated from the host environment. There are multiple ways an adversary escape to a host environment. Examples include creating a container configured to mount the host’s filesystem using the bind parameter, which allows the adversary to drop payloads and execute control utilities such as cron on the host; utilizing a privileged container to run commands or load a malicious kernel module on the underlying host; or abusing system calls such as unshare and keyctl to escalate privileges and steal secrets. Additionally, an adversary be able to exploit a compromised container with a mounted container management socket, such as docker.sock, to break out of the container via a Container Administration Command. also escape via Exploitation for Privilege Escalation, such as exploiting vulnerabilities in global symbolic links in order to access the root directory of a host machine. Gaining access to the host provide the adversary with the opportunity to achieve follow-on objectives, such as establishing persistence, moving laterally within the environment, accessing other containers running on the host, or setting up a command and control channel on the host.},\n",
       " 'T1547.009': {'name': 'Shortcut Modification',\n",
       "  'description': 'create or modify shortcuts that execute a program during system boot or user login. Shortcuts or symbolic links are used to reference other files or programs that will be opened or executed when the shortcut is clicked or executed by a system startup process. abuse shortcuts in the startup folder to execute their tools and achieve persistence. Although often used as payloads in an infection chain (e.g. Spearphishing Attachment), also create a new shortcut as a means of indirection, while also abusing Masquerading to make the malicious shortcut appear as a legitimate program. also edit the target path or entirely replace an existing shortcut so their malware will be executed instead of the intended legitimate program. Shortcuts also be abused to establish persistence by implementing other methods. For example, LNK browser extensions be modified (e.g. Browser Extensions) to persistently launch malware.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['persistence', 'privilege-escalation'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['shortcuts',\n",
       "   'shortcut',\n",
       "   'program',\n",
       "   'executed',\n",
       "   'create',\n",
       "   'execute',\n",
       "   'system',\n",
       "   'startup',\n",
       "   'persistence',\n",
       "   'legitimate'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': create or modify shortcuts that execute a program during system boot or user login. Shortcuts or symbolic links are used to reference other files or programs that will be opened or executed when the shortcut is clicked or executed by a system startup process. abuse shortcuts in the startup folder to execute their tools and achieve persistence. Although often used as payloads in an infection chain (e.g. Spearphishing Attachment), also create a new shortcut as a means of indirection, while also abusing Masquerading to make the malicious shortcut appear as a legitimate program. also edit the target path or entirely replace an existing shortcut so their malware will be executed instead of the intended legitimate program. Shortcuts also be abused to establish persistence by implementing other methods. For example, LNK browser extensions be modified (e.g. Browser Extensions) to persistently launch malware.},\n",
       " 'T1010': {'name': 'Application Window Discovery',\n",
       "  'description': 'attempt to get a listing of open application windows. Window listings convey information about how the system is used. For example, information about application windows be used identify potential data to collect as well as identifying security tooling (Security Software Discovery) to evade. typically abuse system features for this type of enumeration. For example, they gather information through native system features such as Command and Scripting Interpreter commands and Native API functions.',\n",
