       " 'T1027.005': {'name': 'Indicator Removal from Tools',\n",
       "  'description': \"remove indicators from tools if they believe their malicious tool was detected, quarantined, or otherwise curtailed. They modify the tool by removing the indicator and using the updated version that is no longer detected by the target's defensive systems or subsequent targets that use similar systems. A good example of this is when malware is detected with a file signature and quarantined by anti-virus software. An adversary who determine that the malware was quarantined because of its file signature modify the file to explicitly avoid that signature, and then re-use the malware.\",\n",
       "  'tactics': ['defense-evasion'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['detected',\n",
       "   'quarantined',\n",
       "   'malware',\n",
       "   'file',\n",
       "   'signature',\n",
       "   'tool',\n",
       "   'modify',\n",
       "   'systems',\n",
       "   'use',\n",
       "   'remove'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': remove indicators from tools if they believe their malicious tool was detected, quarantined, or otherwise curtailed. They modify the tool by removing the indicator and using the updated version that is no longer detected by the target's defensive systems or subsequent targets that use similar systems. A good example of this is when malware is detected with a file signature and quarantined by anti-virus software. An adversary who determine that the malware was quarantined because of its file signature modify the file to explicitly avoid that signature, and then re-use the malware.},\n",
       " 'T1204.003': {'name': 'Malicious Image',\n",
       "  'description': 'rely on a user running a malicious image to facilitate execution. Amazon Web Services (AWS) Amazon Machine Images (AMIs), Google Cloud Platform (GCP) Images, and Azure Images as well as popular container runtimes such as Docker be backdoored. Backdoored images be uploaded to a public repository via Upload Malware, and users then download and deploy an instance or container from the image without realizing the image is malicious, thus bypassing techniques that specifically achieve Initial Access. This lead to the execution of malicious code, such as code that executes cryptocurrency mining, in the instance or container. also name images a certain way to increase the chance of users mistakenly deploying an instance or container from the image (ex: Match Legitimate Name or Location).',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['execution'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['images',\n",
       "   'image',\n",
       "   'container',\n",
       "   'malicious',\n",
       "   'instance',\n",
       "   'execution',\n",
       "   'amazon',\n",
       "   'backdoored',\n",
       "   'users',\n",
       "   'code'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': rely on a user running a malicious image to facilitate execution. Amazon Web Services (AWS) Amazon Machine Images (AMIs), Google Cloud Platform (GCP) Images, and Azure Images as well as popular container runtimes such as Docker be backdoored. Backdoored images be uploaded to a public repository via Upload Malware, and users then download and deploy an instance or container from the image without realizing the image is malicious, thus bypassing techniques that specifically achieve Initial Access. This lead to the execution of malicious code, such as code that executes cryptocurrency mining, in the instance or container. also name images a certain way to increase the chance of users mistakenly deploying an instance or container from the image (ex: Match Legitimate Name or Location).},\n",
       " 'T1543.005': {'name': 'Container Service',\n",
       "  'description': 'create or modify container or container cluster management tools that run as daemons, agents, or services on individual hosts. These include software for creating and managing individual containers, such as Docker and Podman, as well as container cluster node-level agents such as kubelet. By modifying these services, an adversary be able to achieve persistence or escalate their privileges on a host. For example, by using the docker run or podman run command with the restart=always directive, a container be configured to persistently restart on the host. A user with access to the (rootful) docker command also be able to escalate their privileges on the host. In Kubernetes environments, DaemonSets allow an adversary to persistently Deploy Containers on all nodes, including ones added later to the cluster. Pods also be deployed to specific nodes using the nodeSelector or nodeName fields in the pod spec. Note that containers also be configured to run as Systemd Services.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['persistence', 'privilege-escalation'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['container',\n",
       "   'run',\n",
       "   'cluster',\n",
       "   'services',\n",
       "   'containers',\n",
       "   'docker',\n",
       "   'host',\n",
       "   'agents',\n",
       "   'individual',\n",
       "   'podman'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': create or modify container or container cluster management tools that run as daemons, agents, or services on individual hosts. These include software for creating and managing individual containers, such as Docker and Podman, as well as container cluster node-level agents such as kubelet. By modifying these services, an adversary be able to achieve persistence or escalate their privileges on a host. For example, by using the docker run or podman run command with the restart=always directive, a container be configured to persistently restart on the host. A user with access to the (rootful) docker command also be able to escalate their privileges on the host. In Kubernetes environments, DaemonSets allow an adversary to persistently Deploy Containers on all nodes, including ones added later to the cluster. Pods also be deployed to specific nodes using the nodeSelector or nodeName fields in the pod spec. Note that containers also be configured to run as Systemd Services.},\n",
       " 'T1078': {'name': 'Valid Accounts',\n",
       "  'description': 'obtain and abuse credentials of existing accounts as a means of gaining Initial Access, Persistence, Privilege Escalation, or Defense Evasion. Compromised credentials be used to bypass access controls placed on various resources on systems within the network and even be used for persistent access to remote systems and externally available services, such as VPNs, Outlook Web Access, network devices, and remote desktop. Compromised credentials also grant an adversary increased privilege to specific systems or access to restricted areas of the network. choose not to use malware or tools in conjunction with the legitimate access those credentials provide to make it harder to detect their presence. In some cases, abuse inactive accounts: for example, those belonging to individuals who are no longer part of an organization. Using these accounts allow the adversary to evade detection, as the original account user will not be present to identify any anomalous activity taking place on their account. The overlap of permissions for local, domain, and cloud accounts across a network of systems is of concern because the adversary be able to pivot across accounts and systems to reach a high level of access (i.e., domain or enterprise administrator) to bypass access controls set within the enterprise.',\n",
       "  'tactics': ['initial-access',\n",
       "   'persistence',\n",
       "   'defense-evasion',\n",
       "   'privilege-escalation'],\n",
       "  'keywords': ['access',\n",
       "   'accounts',\n",
       "   'systems',\n",
       "   'credentials',\n",
       "   'network',\n",
       "   'adversary',\n",
       "   'abuse',\n",
       "   'privilege',\n",
       "   'compromised',\n",
       "   'bypass'],\n",
       "  'spacy_doc': obtain and abuse credentials of existing accounts as a means of gaining Initial Access, Persistence, Privilege Escalation, or Defense Evasion. Compromised credentials be used to bypass access controls placed on various resources on systems within the network and even be used for persistent access to remote systems and externally available services, such as VPNs, Outlook Web Access, network devices, and remote desktop. Compromised credentials also grant an adversary increased privilege to specific systems or access to restricted areas of the network. choose not to use malware or tools in conjunction with the legitimate access those credentials provide to make it harder to detect their presence. In some cases, abuse inactive accounts: for example, those belonging to individuals who are no longer part of an organization. Using these accounts allow the adversary to evade detection, as the original account user will not be present to identify any anomalous activity taking place on their account. The overlap of permissions for local, domain, and cloud accounts across a network of systems is of concern because the adversary be able to pivot across accounts and systems to reach a high level of access (i.e., domain or enterprise administrator) to bypass access controls set within the enterprise.},\n",
       " 'T1571': {'name': 'Non-Standard Port',\n",
       "  'description': 'communicate using a protocol and port pairing that are typically not associated. For example, HTTPS over port 8088 or port 587 as opposed to the traditional port 443. make changes to the standard port used by a protocol to bypass filtering or muddle analysis/parsing of network data. also make changes to victim systems to abuse non-standard ports. For example, Registry keys and other configuration settings be used to modify protocol and port pairings.',\n",
